<SECOND>AM-Bush-Proposal,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush to Call for Major Chemical Weapons Reductions</HEAD>
<HEAD>Retransmitting to change category code</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, in a major arms control
initiative, will tell the United Nations on Monday that he is
prepared to slash U.S. chemical weapons stockpiles by more than 50
percent provided the Soviet Union make similar reductions in their
own arsenals of the deadly weapons, administration sources said
Sunday night.
   The proposal, in Bush's first speech as president to the U.N.
General Assembly on Monday, is part of a stepped-up U.S. drive to
slow or even stop the spread of chemical weapons around the world.
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III informed Soviet Foreign
Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze of the president's intention in
their talks over the weekend in Jackson Hole, Wyo. There the two
sides agreed on a two-stage U.S.-Soviet program to exchange
information about their chemical weapons and to inspect each
other's plants and arsenals.
   But, the sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the
superpowers were faced with the bigger problem of halting the
spread of the weapons to other countries, including in stabile
regimes in the Third World. Some two dozen countries are believed
to possess chemical weapons or have the capacity to produce them.
   First disclosure of Bush's initiative came in Monday's editions
of the New York Times. The sources, confirming the thrust of the
newspaper's account, said Bush also would suggest sanctions against
countries which proceed with chemical weapons production.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
