<FILEID>AP-NR-09-24-89 1130EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Democrats-Bush Bjt   09-24 0888</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Democrats-Bush, Bjt,860</SECOND>
<HEAD>As Bush's Popularity Soars, Democrats Again Search for Their Own
Identity</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At a private meeting of House Democratic
leaders last week, national party chairman Ronald H. Brown rose to
apologize for recent speeches taking lawmakers to task for being
too cozy with President Bush.
   But some Democrats on Capitol Hill don't think the party chief
had anything to apologize for.
   As they head for a confrontation this week with Bush over the
capital gains tax rate _ a test that has split the party _ many are
concerned that Bush has lulled them into complacency and succeeded
in blurring the ideological lines between Democrats and Republicans.
   ``I've had a feeling for some years that on economic issues
we've in a sense become one party in America,'' said Rep. Dan
Glickman, D-Kan. ``In a sense we've picked up the values of Ronald
Reagan.''
   Watching Bush sail along with extraordinarily high approval
ratings in the polls, Democrats also are looking bleakly ahead to
elections in which they seem unable to define themselves.
   Brown's chiding of congressional Democrats, ``in all candor, may
have provided a little catalyst for us to see where we're going,''
said Glickman.
   Speaking of Bush, North Dakota Democrat Rep. Byron Dorgan joked
morosely: ``We've got him where he wants us.''
   But as if to illustrate the problem the party faces in crafting
united positions, not all congressional Democrats agree with that
assessment.
   ``For any Democrat to imply that we've not made our positions
clear is just totally an astonishing statement,'' said Rep. William
Gray, D-Pa., the House majority whip. In a pointed comment aimed at
Brown, he added: ``I would urge fellow Democrats to pay a little
more attention.''
   The coming week will be a crucial, high-stakes test for the
Democratic leaders in Congress. It reminds some of 1981, the first
year of Reagan's presidency, when the GOP exploited divisions among
Democrats to roll over Capitol Hill on its tax and budget
priorities.
   This time, the test will come on Bush's plan to reduce the
capital gains tax rate. House Democrats propose instead to raise
the income tax rate on the wealthiest Americans, and use part of
the money to pay for an expansion of tax breaks on Individual
Retirement Accounts, portraying the choice as one of the middle
class versus the wealthy. But getting Democrats to line up behind
the alternative has proven to be a hard sell.
   ``There's a schizophrenia within the party,'' said Rep. Leon
Panetta, D-Calif. ``One group is trying to run away from the tax
issue, and ... the other is trying to urge the courage to confront
that issue. ... It's really '81 all over again. This is the crucial
week for the leadership.''
   Brown's worry is that Democrats, after losing five of the last
six presidential elections, are headed for failure again in 1992
unless they begin now to draw sharp philosophical lines between
themselves and Bush. That conclusion grows out of meetings with
local party officials across the country during his first seven
months as chairman of the Democratic National Committee, said DNC
spokesman Mike McCurry.
   ``The art of politics is presenting a choice to Americans about
two different views of the future,'' McCurry said.
   ``The Republicans know how to evoke passion, to push the hot
button in the voter's chest,'' Dorgan said. ``We've forgotten how
to do that.''
   But Brown's call for lawmakers to ``start preaching the
Democratic gospel'' annoyed top leaders in Congress, the party's
power base. As the majority on Capitol Hill, Democratic lawmakers
feel caught between the need to confront Bush and the necessity to
compromise to fulfill their responsibility for helping govern the
nation. And they believe the party can gain little by pursuing
confrontation for its own sake.
   ``A legislature by its nature speaks with many voices, so it's
difficult to have a single Democratic alternative,'' said Sen. Bill
Bradley, D-N.J., who said lawmakers have to worry about alienating
Republicans whose votes they need. ``The sharper the differences,
the more difficult it is to get 50 votes'' to pass a bill in the
Senate.
   Like Gray, many Democrats argue that the party already has laid
out a long list of issues where it is picking fights with the White
House. The list includes the war on drugs, where Sen. Robert Byrd,
D-W.Va., has proposed to spend significantly more than Bush wanted;
boosting Bush's figure for aid to the new non-communist-dominated
government of Poland; and criticism of ``timid'' presidential
leadership in policy on arms control and Eastern Europe.
   Republicans, so far, purport not to be worried.
   ``You talk about the tax-and-spend Democrats,'' said House GOP
whip Newt Gingrich of Georgia. ``What's their answer on drugs?
Spend more money. What's their answer on Poland? Spend more money.
What's their answer on the tax fight? Raise taxes. ... It tells you
how far out of touch Congress has gotten with the American people.''
   While Brown may have a legitimate gripe with Congress, said Sen.
Sam Nunn, D-Ga., it is impossible to begin setting the stage for a
campaign for the White House this early. ``You don't do that, and
get the public's attention, until you have a candidate and you're
running for election,'' he said. ``Most of the public is not tuned
in.''
</TEXT>
