<FIRST>u i AM-Quebec     09-24 0650</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Quebec,0669</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quebec Voters Again Ponder Sovereign Status</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Whether to spin off from the rest of the country
and form a new nation will once again be on the minds of many
voters Monday when Canada's only predominately French-speaking
province elects a new government.
   Premier Robert Bourassa is seeking another majority for his
Liberal Party, which smashed the nationalist Parti Quebecois four
years ago when it won 99 of the 122 seats in the provincial
assembly.
   Bourassa is touting a 4 percent annual economic growth rate, the
creation of 233,000 new jobs and the social stability that has
lasted most of his term.
   But the idea of separatism for Quebec, thought to have been put
to rest in a 1980 referendum in whichi 60 percent of the voters
rebuffed it, has proved surprisingly enduring.
   Jacques Parizeau of the Parti Quebecois has campaigned
vigorously on a platform based on eventual independence for the
province, and turned out consistently enthusiastic crowds.
   A range of public opinion polls show, however, little likelihood
that the nationalist party will end up with more than the 42
percent of the popular vote that would increase its presence in the
assembly or put a Liberal majority at risk.
   ``The conventional wisdom was that Quebecers were no longer
interested in independence,'' Parizeau said in an interview with
the national news weekly Maclean's. ``But when the question started
being asked again in public opinion polls, it suddenly dawned on
people that support for sovereignty has stayed at roughly 40
percent _ the same as it was in the 1980 referendum results.''
   The Parti Quebecois won 38.7 percent of the popular vote in the
December 1985 provincial election.
   Bourassa's support among Quebec's English-speaking minority,
which traditionally votes Liberal, may be hurt by his refusal in
December to allow more than a token change in provincial laws
restricting commercial signs to the French language.
   ``I came up with a pragmatic solution taking into account
cultural insecurity on the one side and the issue of individual
rights on the other,'' he told Maclean's just before the election.
``If there is a minimum of good faith on both sides, I still
believe there is an acceptable way of facing the challenges of the
1990s.''
   His compromise solution allowed bilingual signs only indoors as
long as the French-language portion was significantly larger than
the English.
   Quebec, Canada's largest and second-most populous province with
6.5 million people, is 81 percent French-speaking.
   Supporters of language restrictions argue they are necessary to
protect French and Quebec's special culture surrounded by English
elsewhere in North America.
   A small Equality Party was formed to campaign against the
language restrictions and could win a seat in Montreal's affluent
Westmount district, a stronghold of English-speaking Quebec. Irate
English-speakers also could cut into the Liberals' showing simply
by staying home.
   Bourassa's term before the language uproar last winter was
unusually quiet as the province settled into a period of
prosperity, leading to speculation that the Parti Quebecois could
be facing its last days.
   In recent weeks, however, there have been environmental protests
over storage of cancer-causing polychlorinated biphenyls, or PCBs,
and a wave of labor unrest among some 265,000 public sector workers
including nurses, hospital workers and teachers.
   Bourassa was the youngest premier elected in Quebec when he won
the 1970 vote at the age of 36. The Parti Quebecois ousted him at
the height of separatist sentiment in 1976 and kept control of the
provincial government until the December 1985 debacle.
   Parizeau won a Parti Quebecois internal leadership struggle last
year and restored its hard-line platform that includes eventual
presentation of a constitution for an independent Quebec.
   Analysts note it is unlikely to attract any voters other than
the most ardent separatists.
   Bourassa, an economist, is counting on Quebecers being more
interested in pragmatic issues related to prosperity than to
independence.
</TEXT>
