<FIRST>r i AM-Auschwitz-Convent     09-24 0464</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Auschwitz-Convent,0476</SECOND>
<HEAD>Polish Cardinal Says New Prayer Center to Be Built</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Roman Catholic archbishop who had
opposed moving a convent from the Auschwitz death camp said Sunday
that a Vatican statement supporting the relocation probably means
that a new convent will be built.
   Cardinal Franciszek Macharski of Krakow, who on Aug. 8 suspended
plans to build the new center for the Carmelite nuns, made the
announcement in a statement to the official PAP news agency.
   It was the first official reply by the Polish church to the
Vatican statement Tuesday that clearly backed moving the convent _
a decision that was resisted by Macharski and Polish primate
Cardinal Jozef Glemp.
   The Vatican also offered to help pay for construction of the
prayer center at an alternative site farther from the Nazi death
camp in southern Poland, where millions were killed during World
War II.
   On Saturday, leaders of the Roman Catholic Carmelite order in
Rome said they support moving the convent, as many Jewish groups
have demanded.
   Macharski said ``The Holy See's statement ... opens a road
toward resumption of work on the center of information, education,
meeting and prayer in Oswiecim,'' the Polish name of Auschwitz.
   Machaeski gave no indication when work on the new center might
actually begin, and made no direct mention of the nuns. Church
officials have obtained a site for the center about 3,000 feet from
the camp, but have not broken ground.
   Glemp, returning Friday from a trip to Britain where he met with
Jewish leaders, said there was ``significant progress'' toward a
positive settlement of the dispute. A day earlier, Jewish leaders
released a letter signed by Glemp in which he promised the convent
would be moved.
   The presence of the nuns and Christian symbols at the camp where
an estimated 2.5 million were killed simply for being Jews has
angered Jews worldwide and many Christians.
   However, many Poles have opposed moving the nuns, arguing that
their prayers are not harmful and they have the right to honor the
memory of the tens of thousands of Christians who also died in
Auschwitz. Four million people died at the death camp.
   Macharski in 1987 agreed to move the nuns to the new ecumenical
prayer center by February 1989, but the deadline passed.
   On Aug. 8, after a group of Jewish Americans entered the convent
grounds and were subsequently roughed up and dragged away by
workmen at the site, Macharski announced that plans for the new
center were suspended because of the ``aggressive'' atmosphere.
   The debate sharpened again Aug. 26 when Glemp accused Jews of
provoking anti-Semitism in Poland and speaking to Poles as a
``nation elevated over all others.'' The remarks were widely
interpereted as anti-Semitic.
</TEXT>
