<FILEID>AP-NR-09-24-89 1253EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-CongressRdp     09-24 0578</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress Rdp,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>For Congress, Quick Completion of Spending Bills Seems Unlikely</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Assoicated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress moved like a hare last year to finish
all 13 of its annual spending measures before the Oct. 1 start of
the new fiscal year, but this year the tortoise is winning again by
moving the finish line.
   Congress must whittle down the $600 billion worth of spending
measures before Sunday's start of fiscal 1990, but lawmakers will
also be occupied this week with other issues.
   The House weighs a tax bill in what will be a deeply partisan
debate, the Senate Finance Committee continues shaping a revision
of the Medicare catastrophic care program for the elderly, and the
House health and environment subcommittee continues crafting a
clean air bill.
   The spending measures, however, will be a top priority.
Congressional leaders have said repeatedly that one of their goals
for the year is to finish spending work on time.
   ``Slowly and with difficulty'' is how Senate Majority Leader
George Mitchell, D-Maine, described the progress on the spending
measures so far.
   That contrasts with the drama last Sept. 30 when at 11:59 p.m. a
middle-aged clerk who had just dashed the 500 feet from the House
chamber struggled to catch his breath and walked solemnly onto the
Senate floor.
   He delivered a copy of this year's foreign aid spending bill,
which the Senate had approved two minutes earlier. The chamber's
receipt of the measure formally completed its acceptance _ and
clinched the first time in a dozen years that Congress had adopted
all 13 of its annual spending measures on time.
   This year it looks like replacing that clerk with a relay team
of Carl Lewis, Ben Johnson and Mercury himself would do no good.
   So far, just one of the measures has been sent to President Bush
for his signature _ the one financing energy and water programs, a
perennial favorite of lawmakers because it is chock full of
projects for their home districts.
   Working on spending bills is not just a question of dollars.
   The measures contain issues as complex and wide-ranging as the
government itself, each of which pits interest groups and political
philosophies against each other. How should the ban on airline
smoking be extended? Should federal financing for ``obscene'' art
be terminated? Should government abortion restrictions be eased?
   Paramount is the fight between Democrats and Republicans over
how federal anti-drug efforts should be expanded. Both sides have
dug their heels in, believing that voters will reward the party
that delivers them from the problem of illegal drugs and the crime
they create.
   Some extra spending _ $1 billion or $2 billion or so _ is likely
to be devoted to drug initiatives this year, money that will have a
domino effect because it will have to be shifted there from other
programs.
   Republicans have blocked Senate passage of spending bills since
Sept. 14 while the two parties tried working out a compromise
anti-drug package. With talks at an apparent impasse, it is
uncertain whether the GOP will change its position.
   Other than the political embarrassment of failing to complete
its spending work on time, there will be no discernible
consequences should the work be undone as the clock strikes
midnight on Saturday.
   The law imposes no penalties for a missed deadline.
   Anticipating just such a scenario, the House plans on Tuesday to
pass a measure temporarily financing government agencies until
November.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
