<FIRST>r w AM-IMF-WorldBank     09-24 0609</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-IMF-World Bank,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>International Monetary Fund Sees Healthy Slowdown in Rich Countries</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States and other rich industrial
countries will experience a healthy cooling of business growth this
year and next, the International Monetary Fund predicted Sunday.
   ``Projections point to a gradual moderation in the pace of
expansion during 1989 and 1990, following two years of rapid
growth,'' the fund said in its semiannual ``World Economic
Outlook.''
   For this year it sees the United States and 20 other
non-Communist industrial countries increasing their total output by
3.5 percent. That is 0.2 percent higher than its prediction of last
April. Though the fraction seems in percentage terms, the
difference amounts to tens of billions of dollars worth of
additional goods and services for the group.
   In 1990, growth is predicted to be 2.9 percent for the 21
countries.
   For the United States alone, the world's biggest economy, the
slowdown is seen as much greater: 4.4 percent last year, 2.9
percent this year and only 2.1 percent in 1990.
   The most growth is predicted for Japan: 4.9 percent this year
and 4.7 percent in 1990; for West Germany 4 percent and 3 percent;
for France 3.4 and 3; for Italy 3.2 and 2.9 and for Britain 3 and
2.7.
   ``There is no sign of recession _ we do not see it in the
current projections,'' Jacob Frenkel, the fund's research chief,
told reporters.
   He called the slowdown healthy and said he was especially
cheered by the growth of investment in new plants and equipment.
These create additional jobs and production for the future.
   But the report warned that there is still a danger of inflation
if the slowdown it foresees in demand for goods does not appear.
Frenkel urged governments to take care to prevent it.
   ``When you see inflation in the figures, you have lost the
battle,'' he said.
   Frenkel said he is also worried by the imbalances in world trade
_ the huge excess of imports over exports in the United states, and
the reverse situation in Japan and West Germany. The report said
Japan and West Germany should not try to expand right now, but
should be ready if necessary.
   The picture it gave for indebted Third World countries was much
gloomier.
   ``Seven years after the onset of the debt crisis, the prospects
for a sustained improvement in growth remained in doubt for many
developing countries _ in contrast to the more favorable outlook
for those developing countries that have avoided debt-servicing
difficulties and for the industrial nations,'' the report said.
   It calculated that production in countries having trouble with
their debt grew by only 2 percent last year. Since population in
those countries grows as fast or faster, that meant no meaningful
increase in average income and in many an actual decline.
   The report gave little attention to Treasury Secretary Nicholas
F. Brady's proposal for reducing the Third World's $1.3 trillion
debt, though it said the growing importance of debt reduction _
along with new lending _ should promote growth.
   ``It is important to realize that debt reduction is no panacea
and that strong adjustment measures remain the key to fundamental
improvements in economic performance,'' it said.
   Frenkel said debt reduction is justified only by improved
policies on the part of debtor governments. He emphasized the
importance of new lending. Major U.S. banks have recently been
increasing their reserves to cushion losses from Third World debt,
a move widely interpreted as indicating their unwillingness to make
new loans.
   ``There is no way you can forget new lending,'' Frenkel said.
``It must be part of future packages.''
</TEXT>
