<FIRST>r i AM-StThomas     09-24 0483</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-St Thomas,0496</SECOND>
<HEAD>St. Thomas Fears Storm Stigma Will Scare Tourists</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PIERRE-YVES GLASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE AMALIE, U.S. Virgin Islands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unlike its
devastated sister island of St. Croix, St. Thomas escaped the worst
of Hurricane Hugo. But merchants still fear the storm still could
damage the tourism industry.
   Two main hotels of this U.S. territory, the V.I. and the Point
Pleasant, were destroyed and most of the 24 others were damaged.
But the Hoteliers Association said Friday they would be repaired in
time for the winter tourist season.
   ``The question is, will the travel trade send people down
here?'' said Jim Graves, co-owner of the 167-room Bluebeard's
Castle. ``People will think the V.I. got blown away by a hurricane
and won't want to come.''
   The roof of his hotel was partially blown away, windows were
shattered and rugs and furniture drenched. He estimated damage at
several million dollars.
   As on St. Croix to the south, all the trees on St. Thomas'
once-lush tropical hills were stripped of leaves and turned into a
brown wasteland. Officials said four to six people were killed in
St. Croix, but no deaths have been reported in St. Thomas.
   Some homes here lost roofs and windows. Yachts were blown out of
Charlotte Amalie Bay onto the wharf and shore, and power and water
services still were absent on most of the island Saturday.
   But most of the colorful, 19th-century Danish-style buildings in
downtown Charlotte Amalie escaped heavy damage, and streets were
clean.
   Three cruise ships visited the capital's harbor Friday, the
first since the storm. Normally, two or three visit daily.
   St. Thomas and St. Croix share about equally the Virgin Islands'
106,000 population. About 2,000 people live on the other main
island in the group, St. John, two-thirds of which is a national
park.
   Tourism is the main industry of the Virgin Islands, with 1.5
million visitors a year spending more than $500 million.
   At the V.I. Hotel, manager Jose R. Salas said that even though
hotels could be repaired by December, tourists might avoid the
Virgin Islands this season.
   But the 200-room hotel, on a hill overlooking Charlotte Amalie,
appeared a total loss. A dozen demolished cars and huge wooden and
concrete chunks of roof littered the parking lot. Most rooms, the
lobby and ballroom were gutted.
   ``This was a penthouse suite,'' Salas said, opening a door that
presented, instead of a room, a panoramic view of the city.
   He estimated damage at $10 million, and said he hoped the hotel
would reopen with 170 restored rooms in time for the winter season.
   Few stores were looted here, unlike on St. Croix. Gerald
Connolly, local coordinator of the Federal Emergency
Administration, said there was little looting because damage was
less severe.
   ``St. Thomas residents always knew they were able to go to the
store and get a cold beer,'' Connolly said.
</TEXT>
