<FIRST>r a AM-SchoolWalkout     09-24 0537</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-School Walkout,0552</SECOND>
<HEAD>Utah Teachers Vote For Statewide Walkout Monday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Utah's public school teachers have voted
to hold a statewide walkout Monday to demonstrate to legislators
that pleas for more education funds cannot be ignored.
   Legislators fueled the revolt last week by passing a tax cut
instead of diverting money from a $94 million state surplus to
education.
   Teacher representatives from the state's 44 school districts
unanimously approved the action Saturday during an emergency
meeting called by the Utah Education Association following a
wildcat walkout in four of the state's largest districts a day
earlier.
   UEA President James Campbell criticized Gov. Norm Bangerter, who
outraged educators Friday by telling them to ``take a couple of
aspirin and go back to work.''
   ``The governor is wrong when he thinks aspirin can cure the
problems with education in this state,'' said Campbell, who passed
out aspirin bottles at the meeting. ``Aspirin will not cure
overcrowded classrooms. Aspirin will not cure lack of materials,
lower teacher-per-pupil ratios and lower salaries.''
   Teachers' pay in Utah ranks 43rd in the nation, $4,500 less than
the average national salary of $29,400, the association says.
   The revolt started Friday in the Davis School District when high
school teachers there walked out of class. By the end of the day,
the wildcat walkouts had affected four districts.
   Monday's planned one-day walkout will mean no classes in Utah's
800 public and vocational schools, providing a holiday for some
435,000 students and a day without pay for 20,000 teachers and
school employees.
   The teachers called on their counterparts at the state's nine
colleges and universities to join them and scheduled a rally Monday
in Salt Lake City. They also asked Utah residents to support them
Monday by driving with headlights on and urging Bangerter to veto
the tax cut.
   They pressed for a meeting of education leaders, legislators
from both major parties and a neutral mediator to set priorities
for education before January's general legislative session.
   James Moss, state superintendent of public instruction, appeared
resigned to more walkouts before the vote was taken but urged
teachers to consider alternative measures.
   Bangerter's chief of staff, Bud Scruggs, said teachers were
taking the tax cut too seriously and that last week's special
session was intended to get it ``out of the way'' so lawmakers
could concentrate on spending during the upcoming general session.
   ``We are sensitive to the teachers and we are proud of the
teachers. We understand their frustration. They have more of an
ally in Governor Bangerter than they're willing to realize,'' he
said.
   Campbell said he doubts lawmakers can ignore the uprising, but
he said teachers have been told before that education needs would
be met.
   ``Come January, if we don't get education resolved like we think
it should, it could get much bigger,'' he said.
   The teachers are seeking a 5 percent standard of living raise,
more money for textbooks and supplies and a commitment to education
as the state's top priority.
   Teachers last walked off the job in Utah in 1964 for essentially
the same reasons cited now. The action lasted two days and resulted
in more funds for library services, personnel and equipment, plus
general salary increases.
</TEXT>
