<FILEID>AP-NR-09-24-89 1427EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Refugees     09-24 0676</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Refugees,0694</SECOND>
<HEAD>East German Arrivals Near 20,000</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two weeks after Hungary opened its
western border to East German refugees, arrivals in West Germany
are nearing 20,000 with no apparent end in sight.
   The migration has exceeded West German expectations. Government
spokesman Hans Klein predicted earlier this month that up to 15,000
or 20,000 East Germans vacationing in Hungary were waiting for a
chance to flee their homeland.
   The Bonn government's earlier estimate that 100,000 East Germans
could emigrate or escape to West Germany this year was exceeded by
mid-September, and officials now say the exodus could reach as high
as 200,000 by year's end.
   West German border guards said that as of noon Sunday, 19,650
East Germans had fled through Hungary to West Germany since Sept.
10, and that the total would no doubt exceed 20,000 by Monday
morning.
   Another 900 East Germans were occupying Bonn's embassies in
Prague, Czechoslovakia, and Warsaw, Poland, demanding passage to
West Germany. And Austrian officials reported 819 East Germans
crossed over from Hungary overnight en route to West Germany,
another surge in the daily stream that shows no signs of ebbing.
   Sunday newspapers hinted that a solution to the embassy
occupations may be in the works, because East Germany wants the
refugee crisis cleared up by Oct. 7, when the hard-line Communist
state celebrates its 40th anniversary.
   Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev will visit East Berlin for
the festivities, and continued strife within the Warsaw Pact would
cast a shadow over the official events.
   While Hungary, Poland and the Soviet Union have swept away the
vestiges of Stalinism, the East German state under the leadership
of ailing, 77-year-old Erich Honecker has refused to loosen the
Communist Party's grip on all aspects of life there.
   Gorbachev, who espouses non-interference in the affairs of other
nations, has been silent over East German intransigence on reform
and the refugee issue that has distanced Hungary from its East-bloc
allies.
   The Hamburg-based Bild am Sonntag newspaper said a face-saving
plan had been worked out that would allow the East Germans holed up
in Warsaw to leave on special travel passes for undisclosed
locations, from which they could later leave for West Germany.
   The weekly news magazine Der Spiegel, in its edition released
Sunday, speculated that the East Germans would leave by ship from
the Polish port of Gdynia and travel to Stockholm, and from there
be flown to West Germany.
   Bild am Sonntag said East Berlin was insisting that such a
resolution be a ``one-time, humanitarian action.''
   The newspaper did not identify its sources, and Bonn government
officials declined to comment on the reported plan.
   ``The main difficulty is, according to diplomats, how it can be
guaranteed that Poland will not become a continually open door as
is the case with Hungary,'' the newspaper reported.
   An attorney acting on Honecker's behalf met two days ago with
West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl's chief of staff, Rudolf
Seiters, to discuss the developments that have forced Bonn to shut
its embassies in Prague and Warsaw for now.
   More than 700 East Germans are packing the mission in Prague,
and another 200 are sheltered at the embassy in Warsaw, awaiting a
diplomatic solution to their demands to emigrate.
   Poland has shown reluctance to emulate Hungary's bold action in
letting the East Germans go west without permission of their
government. And Czechoslovakia has been even slower than East
Germany to loosen travel and emigration restrictions.
   The numbers occupying the embassies in Prague and Warsaw have
grown by 50 to 100 per day over the past week, indicating, along
with the steady flow through Hungary, continued interest among East
Germans in joining the westward caravan.
   East Germans need no special permission to travel to
Czechoslovakia, and visits to Poland are also much easier to
arrange than trips to the West or permission to emigrate.
   The Hungarian newspaper Nepszabadsag reported Saturday that 951
East Germans have escaped across the Czechoslovak-Hungarian border
to travel on to Austria and West Germany.
</TEXT>
