<FILEID>AP-NR-09-24-89 1456EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-GreenRiver     09-24 0774</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Green River,0795</SECOND>
<HEAD>Green River Investigators Need More Time As `Viable Suspect' Is Transferred</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM KLAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A ``viable suspect'' in the Green River serial
murder case is due to get out of jail Monday, but authorities say
they need more time to investigate him and will try to keep him
incarcerated on federal charges in another part of the state.
   William Jay Stevens II, 38, is scheduled to leave King County
Jail after completing the remainder of a sentence for a 1979
burglary and for his 1981 escape from a work release center.
   But the Green River police task force will know where to find
the onetime law student, at least until later in the week. Stevens
is being transferred to Spokane County Jail in eastern Washington
to face federal charges of possessing a firearm while a fugitive in
the burglary case. Those charges carry a potential prison term of
up to 10 years.
   No charges have been filed against Stevens in the Green River
killings, the nation's worst known unsolved serial-murder case.
Stevens has denied he is the killer, and his family members have
produced documents that they say show he was on vacation with the
killings began.
   The case is named for the stream south of Seattle where the
first five victims were found. The killer is blamed for killing 40
young women, most of them linked to prostitution, from 1982 to 1984
in the Seattle and Portland, Ore., areas. Eight missing women also
are believed to be Green River victims.
   Stevens was identified as a ``viable suspect'' in an affidavit
used in July to obtain a search warrant of two Spokane residences
where he lived. It was during those searches that most of the
mounds of evidence that investigators are sifting through was found.
   ``We are not done; we're still working on it,'' King County
Capt. Robert Evans, the task force commander, said Thursday of the
probe that has kept 12 investigators busy since January.
   ``We need another 10 days or two weeks to get through what we
are evaluating. ... The decision would be to determine whether this
person is a murder suspect or merely a victim of some bizarre
circumstances.''
   After he gets to Spokane, Stevens could be released on bail on
the federal charges when a detention hearing is held, probably
later in the week, but prosecutors said they would fight that.
   ``We will vigorously argue that he be detained, given his past
history of jumping (bail) in King County,'' said U.S. Attorney John
Lamp in Spokane.
   Stevens, a fourth-year Gonzaga University law student, was
arrested in Spokane in January after a tip following a syndicated
television show about the Green River killings. When authorities
realized he was a longtime fugitive in the burglary case, they were
able to jail him even though they didn't have the evidence to
charge him in the Green River case.
   After the search warrants were issued in July, authorities
seized dozens of boxes of items, police uniforms and badges,
license plates, a complete undercover police car with municipal
license plates, and 1,800 videotapes, some of them pornographic,
from homes in Spokane where Stevens had lived.
   Investigators had theorized that the Green River killer, or
killers, used police equipment to gain the trust of victims.
   Authorities have been trying to determine Stevens' activities
after his 1981 escape to 1985, when he enrolled at Gonzaga Law
School and began living with his parents in Spokane.
   Evans said Stevens, under one of his many assumed names, even
bought a house in Portland during that time. And once, he said,
Stevens got authorities in Spokane to issue him a special license
plate by passing himself off as the police chief of a small town.
   ``Somebody has got to wonder what he's going to do with this,''
he said.
   Other jurisdictions also may charge Stevens, on crimes such as
car theft.
   Craig Beles, attorney for Stevens, said the attention given
Stevens makes him especially vulnerable for lesser charges.
   ``When you place someone's life under a microscope like that,
you are likely to find something,'' he said. ``There is some
concern ... that perhaps more minor charges are being used to hold
an individual until a larger investigation is completed.''
    As investigators continued examining evidence, Evans said he
continues to hope for that one detail that will put everything
together.
   ``The hard police work is being done and has been done,'' he
said. ``It's going to take a break.''
   ``It could be someone we've already looked at, and there is one
small piece of the puzzle missing,'' Evans said.
</TEXT>
