<FIRST>u i AM-Poland-Media     09-24 0515</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Media,0534</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Solidarity TV Chief Promises Honest Airwaves</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Solidarity journalist named to run the
state broadcast media after four decades of Communist control said
Sunday he wants to usher in ``honest, non-partisan and
professional'' programming.
   Andrzej Drawicz, 57, a former political prisoner specializing in
Soviet affairs, was appointed Saturday by Prime Minister Tadeusz
Mazowiecki to chair the state Radio-Television Committee.
   In a telephone interview, Drawicz said he accepted the
appointment with ``a feeling of humbleness combined with
resignation,'' mainly out of respect and friendship for Mazowiecki,
another veteran journalist who is leading the East bloc's first
non-Communist government.
   The Communist Party strongly defended its monopoly over state
broadcasting as recently as this spring, but ceded it in principle
last month during talks on forming Mazowiecki's Solidarity-led
coalition government.
   Drawicz's committee oversees administration of broadcasting on
Poland's two national television channels and four radio channels.
There are no legal independent broadcasters in Poland, although
there are plans to permit private radio stations.
   The new media chief said his post ``does not lie in the main
sphere of my interests and I am not interested in making a
political career. ... But I came to the conclusion that when one
must, one must.''
   It is too soon to speak about concrete plans, he said.
   ``Generally speaking ... the television which has been an
instrument of one party's influence on society should be changed
into society's property, the property of the population, acting in
favor of this population,'' he said.
   It ``should be non-partisan, although it may present different
views through the statements of different people, a whole range of
views. That is its right and even its duty, to mirror society's
situation.
   ``But as such it should be honest, non-partisan and
professional.''
   Drawicz noted the poor financial situation of state television
and radio, which he said ``is as difficult as our general
situation'' of economic crisis.
   Some Solidarity activists have urged that, as a symbol of
Poland's dramatic political transformation, current news announcers
be replaced.
   ``Of course there are elements irritating society,'' Drawicz
said of possible personnel changes. ``We will have to think about
how to eliminate these elements without harming those who are not
guilty.''
   The radio-television committee is to be transferred from direct
Cabinet control to supervision by the Sejm, or lower house of
parliament, where the Solidarity-led coalition forms a majority.
Although chaired by Drawicz, it will include members of all
political parties, including the Communists.
   Unlike his predecessor, former government spokesman Jerzy Urban,
Drawicz does not to have Cabinet rank. This reflects Mazowiecki's
view that his new government should have nothing like a minister of
information shaping public opinion.
   Drawicz said he will begin his duties Monday.
   Drawicz, whose opposition activities date back to the Committee
for Defense of Workers in the mid-1970s, is a specialist in Soviet
affairs with no significant experience in television or radio.
   Along with thousands of Solidarity supporters, he was jailed
after martial law was imposed in December 1981 to crush the
independent trade union.
</TEXT>
