<DOCNO> AP890924-0033 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-24-89 1515EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-CocaineSwallowers     09-24 0615</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cocaine Swallowers,0631</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Seizures Involving Drug Swallowers Surge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SANDRA WALEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Customs agents, used to seeing travelers use
exotic methods to smuggle drugs into this country, are noticing an
increase in the dangerous practice of swallowing cocaine to avoid
detection.
   Plainclothes inspectors roving the huge customs area at Miami
International Airport are capturing an average of a half-dozen of
what they called ``internals'' every week, said senior customs
inspector George Dickinson.
   The swallowers are taken to a hospital prison ward to pass the
sealed pellets of cocaine, with the help of laxatives.
   In one recent week, among those taken into custody were: a
45-year-old man who arrived on a flight from Bogota, Colombia,
after swallowing 120 packets totaling a kilo of cocaine, or about
2.2 pounds; two men on another flight from Bogota who ingested 226
drug packets between them; and two men who flew in from Jamaica
with a total of 100 packets of cocaine and hashish in their systems.
   So far this year, 64 people ``packed from top to bottom with
pellets'' have been taken into custody compared with 25 for all of
last year, Dickinson said. The majority of drug seizures by agents
at the airport in the past three months have been from internals,
he said.
   ``It's becoming more prevalent due to extensive outbound
searches in Colombia,'' he said.
   Colombian authorities stepped up their pat-downs of U.S.-bound
travelers about six to eight months ago, Dickinson said, prompting
many would-be smugglers to stop carrying drugs on their person.
   Most of the defendants accused of smuggling drugs internally are
poor, illiterate Colombian citizens who can expect to earn about
$2,000 for successfully delivering the drugs for someone else, said
Dickinson.
   ``Money is the motivation,'' said John Fernandes, spokesman for
the U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration.
   Miami authorities recovered 116 pellets from a Colombian woman
who was seven months pregnant when she swallowed nearly a kilo of
cocaine to bring into the United States. In July, Iveth Rocha, 23,
was sentenced to 40 years in prison after being convicted of drug
trafficking.
   Officials aren't certain how much cocaine is getting in via
swallowers. But customs agents believe they have developed a keen
eye for spotting potential smugglers by looking for signs of
unusual behavior or nervousness.
   Once people are targeted, they are taken aside for an in-depth
interview and a decision is made whether to transport them to
Jackson Memorial Hospital to recover the drugs if they don't
produce them at the airport.
   ``When we started to see this 10 years ago, the packets were
hand-made things that tended to dissolve or break apart,'' said Dr.
Kathleen Schrank, director of Jackson's emergency care center.
``Things have gotten a whole lot more sophisticated.''
   The cocaine is usually compressed into a hard cylinder, sealed
in plastic and wrapped in condoms or the tips of surgical gloves.
The reinforced packets have cut down on the number of deaths that
resulted from very pure cocaine escaping into the gastrointestinal
tract.
   ``Uncut cocaine in that potency, when it escapes into the
system, is lethal,'' said U.S. Customs spokesman Cliff Stallings.
   Those who wait for symptoms to develop before they seek medical
attention may be too late, said Charles Wetli, Dade County's deputy
chief medical examiner.
   Alfredo Romero, 44, was visiting his brother in Hialeah last
month when he started complaining of an upset stomach and began
vomiting the day after arriving from Colombia. The next day he was
found unconscious on the living room floor and was pronounced dead
a short while later.
   An autopsy revealed nearly half a kilo of cocaine in his system;
several packets of cocaine had ruptured.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890924-0034 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-24-89 1517EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-UN-Bush     09-24 0731</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Bush,0753</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Faces Changed United Nations in First Presidential Address</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When President Bush addresses the General
Assembly on Monday, he will stand before an institution that has
changed dramatically since his days as the U.S. representative to
the United Nations.
   Gone are ritual denunciations of the West by Soviet and Third
World speakers. Harmony and cooperation are now the watchwords in
the General Assembly, and most resolutions are adopted by consensus.
   The Soviet Union has emerged as the mover and shaker in
international diplomacy, standing in marked contrast to the Bush
administration's cautious, reactive approach to world affairs.
   Bush aides said Sunday that his first presidential address to
the United Nations will include a major chemical weapons proposal
and a call for international cooperation on drugs, terrorism and
the environment.
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III said the proposal would
``move the world closer to a ban on chemical weapons.''
   But White House officials were tight-lipped on the substance of
the proposal.
   The president also is expected to discuss the moves toward
political and economic reform in Poland and other East bloc
countries.
   Bush's speechwriters completed a draft of his U.N. address
Saturday night following announcement of several accords, and plans
for a superpower summit, after two days of talks between Baker and
Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze.
   Among the accords was an agreement to exchange data on chemical
weapons by the end of the year and allow visits by inspectors of
the other side to stockpiles and plants by June 30. In a second
phase, there would be more intensive on-site inspections of the
submitted data.
   Officials at the U.S. Mission to the United Nations say
privately that they were not consulted about the speech, except to
scour their archives for anecdotal material from Bush's tenure as
the U.S. ambassador in 1971-72.
   That suggests Bush will not respond to the multitude of Soviet
proposals for strengthening the United Nations, many offered by
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev in his speech to the Assembly in
December.
   Gorbachev called for a U.N. peacekeeping force in Afghanistan,
U.N. leadership in banning weapons from space, and in assembling
scientists to solve environmental disasters.
   He also proposed giving the World Court mandatory jurisdiction
in all human rights cases and called for a U.N.-sponsored
conference on solving the Third World's $1.3-trillion debt to the
developed world.
   All these ideas have withered on the vine as the United States
withheld any reaction or counterproposal and the Soviets
characteristically failed to lobby aggressively for them.
   Western diplomats say privately that they expect Bush will
praise the new era of cooperation among the major powers, brought
about by Gorbachev's commitment to restructuring Soviet society and
cooperating with the West whenever possible.
   Bush is also expected to assail the power of the drug lords,
whose power rivals that of the governments of some nations where
they are based.
   U.N. peacekeepers from the past and present won the Nobel Peace
Prize last year for their work. The United States advocates a
strong U.N. role in peacekeeping and Bush is expected to remind the
delegates of that.
   U.N. officials and even U.S. allies in Western Europe note that
Washington still has tight purse strings when the United Nations is
concerned.
   ``The entire international community is encouraging us and
applauding what we are doing,'' Secretary-General Javier Perez de
Cuellar said this week. ``It is easy to applaud; but I would like
them to do what is really their duty _pay their contributions to
our peacekeeping operations.''
   As of the end of last month the United States was over $495
million in arrears on its dues to the regular U.N. budget. That is
about two-thirds of the $688 million in total arrears owed by all
159 member nations. The entire regular U.N. budget is about $776
million a year.
   The United States also owes about $254 million to special
accounts for peacekeeping, which costs the world body about $700
million yearly.
   The Soviet Union is about $7 million in arrears to the regular
budget and owes $211 million for peacekeeping but has been paying
off the peacekeeping debt.
   Bush's administration has asked Congress to pay the arrears, but
due to the federal budget deficit, the United Nations appears
unlikely to receive more than the current year's dues plus current
peacekeeping costs.
</TEXT>
