<FIRST>r p AM-ClevelandMayor     09-24 0772</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cleveland Mayor,0796</SECOND>
<HEAD>Five Compete to Succeed Mayor Voinovich</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS J. SHEERAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five officeholders well-known in Cleveland are
campaigning aggressively to succeed Mayor George Voinovich, who led
the city out of financial default and fought off years of jokes
about its burning river.
   The five will meet in a non-partisan Oct. 3 primary, with the
top two vote-getters meeting in the Nov. 7 general election.
   Voinovich took office Nov. 12, 1979, one year after the city
defaulted under Mayor Dennis Kucinich, a self-styled populist. At
the time, the city's image was in shambles, the result of default
under the youthful Kucinich, who was dubbed ``Dennis the Menace.''
   And then there was the 1969 fire on the oil-slickened Cuyahoga
River, which created the image of a dirty city, the butt of jokes.
   Last year, Voinovich tried unsuccessfully to unseat U.S. Sen.
Howard Metzenbaum, a Cleveland Democrat. He's not running for mayor
again in order to seek the 1990 Republican nomination for governor.
   In the race for his successor, Voinovich endorsed the lone GOP
candidate, Ralph J. Perk Jr., the school board president and son of
a former mayor.
   The other candidates, all Democrats, are Court Clerk Benny
Bonanno, City Council President George Forbes, Cuyahoga County
Commissioner Tim Hagan and state Sen. Michael White.
   Forbes, 59, has served on the City Council since 1963 and has
been its president for 16 years, a role that made him a likely
favorite to make the runoff. Voinovich gave Forbes broad powers to
promote bipartisanship in the city government.
   White, 37, who has served in the state Legislature for six
years, won an endorsement Sunday from The Plain Dealer, Cleveland's
only daily newspaper.
   The five candidates have focused on the issues of jobs,
education and drugs and how to continue the downtown development
that has polished the image of the city of about 536,000 people.
Drug tests for candidates, charges of ethical conflicts and talk of
voting along racial lines also have been prominent.
   Political science professor B. James Kweder of Cleveland State
University expects one white and one black to emerge from the
primary. White and Forbes are black; the others are white.
   ``Blacks vote for blacks, whites vote for whites. They cross
party lines to do that,'' he said.
   The Census Bureau estimates that 49 percent of the population is
black, 45 percent white and 6 percent Hispanic and other minorities.
   Forbes acknowledged that he had little support in the largely
white west side and said race was the reason no white elected
official had endorsed him or White.
   White dismissed Forbes' complaint of racial prejudice, saying
Forbes was hoping to capitalize on racial divisions. White said
endorsements typically follow neighborhood political
considerations, and he noted that no black elected official had
endorsed a white candidate.
   Forbes ran a major voter registration drive, and 70 percent of
the city's 24,000 new voters live in mostly black neighborhoods.
   Robert E. Hughes, chairman of the Cuyahoga County Board of
Elections and the county Republican Party, predicted the turnout in
a black-white runoff could surpass the record 79 percent in 1967,
when Carl B. Stokes became the first black mayor of a major U.S.
city.
   ``You have five people with enormous name recognition, and they
are waging an all-out campaign,'' Hughes said.
   The increasing cocaine problem has made drugs a focus of the
campaign, with Hagan and Bonanno accepting Perk's challenge to take
urine tests. All three said they proved themselves drug-free.
   Forbes has been criticized for his support of five narcotics
detectives acquitted of drug trafficking charges during a 1985
sting operation, in which police recruited a dealer as an informant.
   The informant said police allowed him to continue selling drugs
in an impoverished black neighborhood, a claim denied by police
officials. But blacks were angered.
   Forbes also came under attack when his law firm represented a
tenant group before a public housing agency whose governing board
includes Forbes appointees. Federal officials have called
Cleveland's public housing the most delabidated in the country,
except for Chicago's.
   Forbes began his campaign by apologizing for mistakes, which
included comments considered by some as sexist and tossing a chair
at a City Council colleague.
   He also apologized for a campaign comment that he didn't
``pimp'' his wife like Hagan, who is married to a wealthy woman.
   Hagan, 43, is a self-described liberal and longtime friend of
the Kennedy family.
   Bonanno, 39, who has held five different elective offices; Perk,
44, who is a lawyer in addition to being school board president;
and White all have served on the City Council with Forbes.
</TEXT>
