<FIRST>u i AM-Hugo-Caribbean     09-24 0353</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hugo-Caribbean,0364</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hugo-Damaged Storage Tank Spilling Fuel Oil Into St. Croix Harbor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A utility storage tank damaged by
Hurricane Hugo is spilling 7,000 gallons of fuel oil a day into a
harbor in the U.S. Virgin Islands, the Coast Guard said Sunday.
   The Coast Guard's Marine Safety Office in San Juan said 40,000
gallons of oil have flowed into waters around Christiansted,
capital of St. Croix, since Hugo slammed into the U.S. territory on
Sept. 17.
   The oil is flowing from a storage tank at a Virgin Islands Water
and Power Authority plant containing 1.6 million gallons of No. 6
fuel oil, the Coast Guard said in a statement.
   It said the oil is leaking into earthen containment dikes and
trenches, and then into Christiansted Harbor. Some oil is being
contained within floating booms, and some is free-floating.
Northerly winds have kept the oil from spreading more than about a
quarter-mile from shore.
   ``Because the rate of discharge from the damaged tank has been
steady, the Coast Guard doesn't expect a catastrophic spill from
the tank,'' the statement said. ``However, the containment dikes
and trenches could break at any time.''
   Coast Guard pollution specialists from Mobile, Ala., were
preparing on Sunday to pump oil from the dikes to barges for
removal, so that the leak can be repaired.
   ``The Coast Guard hopes that all the oil can be removed within
the next two days,'' the statement said.
   St. Croix was one of the eastern Caribbean islands hardest-hit
by Hugo along a 500-mile arc from Guadeloupe to Puerto Rico.
   Officials say the storm caused at least 27 deaths and billions
of dollars in damage in the region.
   Much of Puerto Rico, including the San Juan metropolitan area,
remained without running water Sunday. About one-quarter of the
island also was without electricity.
   Otherwise, however, the island was returning to normal, with
nearly all roads cleared and most stores and gas stations open.
   Education Secretary Jose Lema said public schools would reopen
Monday, but he cautioned students not to drinking water from
fountains because of the risk of contamination.
</TEXT>
