<HEAD>Chateau Yquem, Vintage 1811, Fetches $19,800 at Auction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST HOLLYWOOD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A collector shelled out $19,800 to
add a 178-year-old bottle of Chateau Yquem to his collection during
Christie's first West Coast wine auction.
   The daylong event Saturday grossed $654,115, said Shirley
Knudsen, a spokeswoman for the London-based auction house.
   ``The sale has exceeded Christie's expectations,'' Ms. Knudsen
said. ``It shows that the enthusiasm for rare wines is strong in
Southern California.'' As a result, she said, Christie's is
planning a second West Coast wine auction next spring.
   More than 30 private cellars were represented at the auction,
which drew more than 400 bidders.
   A collector from Marina del Rey offered the highest bid of the
day, topping $11,800 paid by a Canadian for an Imperial of 1924
Chateau Mouton-Rothschild and $11,200 by a Sacramento resident for
a rare magnum of Chateau Lafite 1864.
   The three top overall bidders were Southern Californians,
spending $48,000, $46,000 and $31,000, respectively. Ms. Knudsen
would not name the bidders, saying the auction house protects
buyers' privacy.
