<FILEID>AP-NR-09-24-89 2039EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-HUD-Lantos     09-24 0911</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HUD-Lantos,890</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sharp-Tongued Chairman Draws Ire From Lawyers, Praise From Colleagues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   His greetings, without exception, are polite
and eloquent, instructive of his Old World upbringing. But the
courtliness quickly gives way to sarcasm if Tom Lantos is
displeased by what he hears.
   ``This is about as believable as Elvis being seen in a K Mart,''
the California Democrat retorted recently to one witness testifying
before his subcommittee.
   ``If HUD were a bank it would be closed by the FDIC,'' was
another memorable Lantos committee-room response.
   Such quips have become a Lantos trademark as he leads a
congressional investigation of Reagan-era scandals at the
Department of Housing and Urban Development. The review has
transformed the him from a 61-year-old congressman who was little
known outside his California district into one of the most visible
lawmakers on Capitol Hill.
   Lantos quickly seized on an April report that first disclosed
some of HUD's problems, and his success appears to have given
lawmakers who didn't act so fast second thoughts.
   Senate Banking Committee Chairman Donald Riegle, D-Mich., began
a HUD hearing last week with an excuse for not being more active on
the issue, saying the panel had ``put other things aside'' to deal
with the savings and loan bailout.
   ``That job is now done,'' Riegle said in announcing he planned
an exhaustive investigation of his own, with testimony from a long
list of witnesses who already have been summoned by Lantos.
   Lantos' hearing room has been the scene of testimony detailing
the millions made by Republican consultants with access to HUD
officials and the millions lost by HUD because of fraud and
mismanagement. The obscure panel and its chairman have shown no
fear of controversy, issuing a subpoena to force former HUD
Secretary Samuel Pierce to testify this week.
   Critics say Lantos has played politics at the expense of the
rights of some of the subcommittee witnesses.
   ``This is a lawmaker on national television doing things for the
explicit reason of getting votes,'' said Raymond Banoun, who
represents a former top Pierce aide who refused to testify. ``It's
more putting on a show than an investigation.''
   Lantos scoffs at that, saying he has run a ``fair and
professional and bipartisan investigation,'' and a leading
Democratic theorist said criticism of his performance will fall on
deaf ears among the public.
   ``The public is not worrying about the fine legal arguments,''
said political consultant Frank Greer. ``They think this guy should
be going after them for stealing the taxpayers' dollars and putting
them in the pockets of Republican consultants. He has enhanced his
image and the image of the Democratic Party as well.''
   Lantos is clearly relishing the spotlight and boasts that his
subcommittee's work was the impetus for an Office of Management and
Budget directive that all agencies review their management
practices.
   ``What is happening is analogous to you suddenly seeing a
highway patrolman in your rear view mirror and you suddenly start
driving at the proper speed,'' Lantos said. ``My job will be to try
to see to it that this atmosphere is not just a fleeting moment.''
   Lantos professes no interest in parlaying his sudden prominence
into political gain. But colleagues and political analysts say that
at a minimum Lantos has established himself as an effective and
articulate Democratic advocate for clean government.
   ``That's not for me to evaluate,'' was all Lantos would say when
asked whether he had profited politically from the investigation.
   He doesn't need help back home, where he captured more than 70
percent of the vote in his last two re-elections, but Lantos could
benefit in the House when he needs support for legislation.
   ``The way he's conducted the hearings has created a well of
goodwill for him,'' said Greer.
   That Lantos has spent most of his congressional career focusing
on foreign affairs is a product of his childhood. He was born in
Budapest in 1928 and escaped during the World War II Nazi
occupation of Hungary. He was first elected to Congress in 1980 and
is a co-founder of the Congressional Human Rights Caucus.
   But when HUD's inspector general issued a report in April saying
that an agency rent subsidy program appeared riddled with influence
peddling, Lantos jumped on the issue and launched an investigation
that now seems likely to continue into next year.
   He is a former college professor and holds a Ph.D. in economics,
yet at time he has professed to being ``simple'' in asking for more
details. The tactic that has nudged several witnesses into
compelling testimony, including former Interior Secretary James
Watt's admission that he made more than $400,000 in HUD consulting
fees despite no housing background and a Maryland woman's
incredible account of how she kept $5 million in HUD money without
being caught.
   Lantos also has brought theater to the televised hearings, twice
calling witnesses to testify even though he had been told in
advance they would not appear, then looking out in mock disbelief
at the empty witness table.
   Those moments have been followed by tirades directed at the
absent witnesses, including Pierce. Pierce had said he needed more
time to prepare because he had trouble finding a lawyer.
   That was instant fodder for another verbal salvo from Lantos.
   He called Pierce ``capricious'' and ``deceitful'' and
sarcastically dissected the former Cabinet member's excuse.
   ``I can understand not being able to find affordable housing in
Washington,'' said Lantos, ``but not an attorney.''
</TEXT>
