<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     09-24 0380</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0395</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Southern California is in the middle of a
drought and it's a crime to waste water. But who checks up on
violations by the city itself?
   Edwin E. Neumann does, as he surveys his neighborhood almost
daily looking to bust water wasters.
   ``The city asks everyone else to conserve water. Yet it doesn't
follow its own advice,'' he said. ``There's no excuse for things
like this.''
   Neumann has identified dozens of leaky fire hydrants and broken
sprinklers on public greenbelts since launching his one-man patrol.
   He has filed repeated complaints with the city about
street-sweeper drivers who don't close hydrants after filling their
tanks and park workers who carelessly water the sidewalks as well
as their lawns.
   Neumann, 69, a retired high school gardener, started his
campaign after receiving city literature promoting water
conservation.
   His first target was a fire hydrant across the street from the
high school that had been dripping for years.
   Althoug he's a pain to some, other city officials admire
Neumann's tenacity.
   ``I would say he's a value to the city and I'd like to have more
people like him, even if other departments wouldn't,'' said Shirley
Minser, a field deputy for City Councilman Richard Alatorre.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HOMER, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Several hundred people turned out during the
weekend for ``Victoria Day,'' honoring the first woman to run for
president, nearly 50 years before U.S. women won the right to vote.
   Victoria Claflin Woodhull, born Sept. 23, 1838, also reportedly
was the first woman stockbroker on Wall Street and the first woman
to speak before Congress, said organizers of Saturday's event.
   ``Most people do not even know who she is, but she was an
example of courage and leadership,'' said Joseph Berg, president of
the Homer Historical Society.
   Several hundred people gathered at the local library to trade
stories about Ms. Woodhull and buy and sell T-shirts, caps, plates,
bells, postcards and other souvenirs.
   Ms. Woodhull was the candidate of the Equal Rights Party in
1872, receiving only a few thousand votes. One of her election
opponents was then-President Ulysses S. Grant, who was re-elected.
   ``Victoria was a person who believed that blacks and women were
people, just like the Constitution said they were,'' Berg said.
</TEXT>
