<DOCNO> AP890924-0042 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-24-89 1602EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Italy-SovietJews     09-24 0671</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Italy-Soviet Jews,0691</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Jews Hurry to Enter United States Before Deadline</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAPUCINE CARRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Relief organizations are rushing to help thousands
of Soviet Jewish emigrants reach the United States by Sept. 30, the
last day for regulations that allow them to enter relatively easily.
   Immigrant aid organizations are working overtime to prepare
refugee applications for examination at the U.S. Embassy in Rome,
one of the main transfer points for Soviet Jewish refugees.
   Sept. 30 marks the end of the U.S. government's fiscal year and
authorities are studying new limits on Soviet immigration for the
next fiscal year.
   In recent weeks, more than 400 Soviet refugees have filled New
York-bound planes each morning at Rome's Leonardo da Vinci airport,
up from an average of 130 daily in May, according to the U.N.
International Committee for Migration.
   On Thursday, 1,350 Soviet Jewish refugees are to leave Rome for
New York _ 480 on a single plane.
   ``It's total chaos,'' said an employee of the U.N. organization
last Thursday, as she urged refugees to bring their luggage to the
check-in counter.
   Most Soviet Jews leave their country on an Israeli visa. But
once they get to Rome or Vienna, many apply for U.S. visas.
   Until October 1988, all Soviet Jews were granted U.S. refugee
status on the grounds they were the object of persecution at home.
The U.S. government pressed Moscow to allow greater Jewish
emigration.
   As U.S.-Soviet relations improved and Soviet President Mikhail
Gorbachev put more liberal policies into effect, the number of Jews
allowed to emigrate mushroomed from a few hundred a year to 33,444
in the first eight months of 1989.
   The United States increased its quota on Soviet refugees from
25,000 to 43,500 for fiscal 1989. But at the same time, it began to
insist last year that applicants prove their fears of persecution
were well-founded.
   Because of the change, the visa refusal rate in Rome has been
``around 20 percent,'' said U.S. Embassy spokesman Michael Hahn.
   The U.S. State Department expects an overwhelming 250,000
Soviets to apply for entry to the United States in 1990. But for
the new fiscal year, a proposal is being studied that would give
refugee status only to Soviet Jews with relatives or other ties to
the United States.
   Applicants denied refugee status would still be able to get a
visa, but they would have to find a sponsor to guarantee their
financial security and wait longer to become permanent residents.
   Agencies helping Soviet Jews are afraid the new regulations will
drive up the visa refusal rate. They have speeded up immigration
applications to fill the fiscal 1989 quota for Soviet refugees,
which had not yet been reached last week, according to Hahn.
   The organizations also fear cuts in funding for resettlement, so
they are trying to hasten the departure of all Soviets who have
been accepted as U.S. refugees.
   ``We're trying to send away as many people as possible before
the October deadline,'' said a representative of the New York-based
Hebrew Immigration Aid Society in Rome, who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   ``Everybody is concentrating on making these people leave, so we
don't even have time to do the statistics,'' she said, when asked
about the number of departures expected in September.
   Peter Schatzer, chief of mission in Rome for the International
Committee for Migration, said that many details can delay
departures.
   For example, the refugees must undergo a medical examination
before leaving. ``But in August, most Italian doctors are on
holidays,'' he said.
   The final decision on the new U.S. immigration regulations for
Soviet Jews is expected next month.
   On Thursday, like most recent mornings, Rome's airport resembled
a Moscow train station. Refugees waited anxiously at a meeting
point to receive their U.S. visas. In a corner, a family cried: the
poodle could not travel in the cabin.
   A middle-aged Soviet man with a bewildered look walked through
passport control with his wife and three children.
   ``So now we are free,'' he said softly.
</TEXT>
