<FIRST>r a AM-Hugo-Church     09-24 0488</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hugo-Church,0504</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hugo's Victims Pause During Cleanup to Hold Church Services</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hugo, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TRIP DuBARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C.(AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Churchgoers picked their way through
rubble Sunday to get to St. Philip's Episcopal Church, where the
choir read hymnals by candlelight and sang with a piano because the
electric organ was useless.
   ``If Hurricane Hugo has taught us anything, let it teach us
humility, how much we know our need for God,'' said the Rev. James
E. Hampton.
   One side of the 25-foot door was blown out of the church, whose
congregation dates back more than 300 years, and a copper roof was
peeled off a chapel by Hugo's fury. About 250 people walked or
eased their cars past downed palmetto trees and broken bricks.
   Fallen oaks rested on a portion of a wrought-iron fence. The
doors to the church were propped open for light because the
electricity still has not been restored.
   ``If God is good, why does he allow bad storms to take place?''
Hampton asked the congregation, some of them dressed in cleanup
jeans while others wore their Sunday finest.
   Perhaps, he said, ``God allowed that hurricane to hit Charleston
dead center because he wanted to punish Charlestonians for their
sins. ... Who knows?''
   Before the service, the congregation swapped information on how
friends and neighbors weathered the storm.
   By the time the choir and ministers proceeded out in song,
several in the congregation were wiping tears from their eyes.
   Jimmy Bailey, the Democrat who represents the district in the
state Legislature, said the service had special meaning for his
family, and many others.
   ``We have no roof and we've got three feet of water in the
living room,'' Bailey said. ``But we all have what we were born
with and that's good health. ... Anything else is just gravy.''
   Those with gas power offered hot meals and showers. Tom
Johnston, an attorney, offered use of his home to those needing it.
   ``My door is not going to be locked. Feel free to come in and
use it,'' he said.
   At St. Andrew's Episcopal Church in Mount Pleasant, across the
harbor from Charleston, people hugged one another on the portico as
they gathered for morning services. Nearby, massive oaks blocked a
road.
   To the north, 50 churches in the Columbia area asked congregants
to make donations for the hurricane victims this week and next.
   ``The congregation has been asked to bring in food, clothes,
brooms, cleaning supplies, bottled water, bedding _ any household
items that are transportable,'' said LeGrand Cooper, administrator
at the First Presbyterian Church in Columbia. ``We're hearing
reports that people are waiting in line for hours to buy things.
So, we're trying to send items down they can use.''
   The Salvation Army is looking for volunteers to go Charleston
for at least three days to distribute donated items, said Major Ken
Bush of the Salvation Army in Columbia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890924-0044 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-24-89 1840EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-RockyFlats     09-24 0643</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rocky Flats,0664</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Fed Up' DOE Boots Rockwell Following Threat, Lawsuit, Official Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rockwell International Corp., which said it was
withdrawing as operator of the Rocky Flats nuclear weapons plant,
actually was ousted because the government was ``fed up,'' a
federal official said.
   Department of Energy deputy secretary W. Henson Moore said
Rockwell officials did not know of the DOE's intention to sever
ties with the company until Friday morning, The Denver Post
reported in Sunday's editions.
   Official reports Friday had said Rockwell's departure from the
DOE plant was by mutual decision and gave no reason for the move.
   ``This Rockwell incident shows we're not going to be bullied or
buffaloed or scared,'' Moore, second in command at the DOE to
Energy Secretary James Watkins, told the newspaper Saturday.
``We're willing to do exactly what we're doing. We're not going to
tolerate less than the performance we want.''
   The federal government is investigating possible environmental
crimes at Rocky Flats, 15 miles northwest of Denver, which makes
plutonium triggers for thermonuclear boms.
   The plant was raided June 6 by more than 70 federal agents. A
special federal grand jury in Denver is reviewing evidence obtained
during the raid as part of an investigation into the alleged
coverup of illegal hazardous and radioactive waste-disposal
practices.
   Rockwell's ouster stemmed in part from its threat the previous
week to shut down Rocky Flats if the company was not given
protection from prosecution for environmental violations at the
plant, Moore said.
   ``The last straw,'' he said, the step that left the DOE ``fed
up,'' was when Rockwell sued the government Thursday, seeking a
temporary injunction to prohibit such prosecution.
   Rockwell spokesman Dennis Hurtt, reached Sunday by telephone at
home in Denver, said the company had no immediate response to
Moore's comments.
   Moore said Watkins had contacted EG&amp;G Inc. of Wellesley, Mass.,
last Monday, to see if the $1.4 billion scientific engineering
company was interested in replacing Rockwell at Rocky Flats. The
company was named Friday as the new Rocky Flats contractor.
   EG&amp;G already operates the Idaho National Engineering Laboratory,
which operates test reactors; the Nevada Test Site where nuclear
weapons are tested; and the Mound Facility at Miamisburg, Ohio,
where detonators for nuclear warheads are made.
   Moore said Watkins telephoned Rockwell Chairman Donald Beall on
Friday to notify him of the decision.
   Rockwell was hailed as a white knight when it took over Rocky
Flats from then-beleaguered Dow Chemical in 1975.
   Moore said Saturday that Rockwell received a
``less-than-satisfactory'' performance evaluation _ the worst
evaluation ever given a DOE contractor _ for its operations at
Rocky Flats during the six months ending March 31, 1989. The
company got bonuses nonetheless, but, Moore said, they were about
half of the $4 million to $5 million Rockwell had expected to
receive.
   Under a new DOE performance evaluation system, which gives more
weight to environmental health and safety at its facilities,
Rockwell would have received no bonus at all for those six months,
Moore said.
   Rockwell officials have said they do not plan to drop the
lawsuit against the government.
   Moore called the lawsuit ``meaningless.'' ``We really never did
pay much attention to the lawsuit. Now that they're going to be out
of the contract, what's the point?'' he asked.
   Representatives of EG&amp;G were to arrive Monday to begin the
management transition.
   Moore said Rockwell's five-year, $2.5 billion contract to
operate the plant was being sweetened to appease EG&amp;G concerns
about taking over the troubled plant.
   ``Obviously, EG&amp;G officials have concerns about their company's
equity,'' Moore said.
   EG&amp;G also has had environmental problems and violations at DOE
facilities it manages.
   Moore, however, said most of the problems at those facilities
were inherited by EG&amp;G.
   ``They're a first-class company with a tremendous amount of
experience with nuclear matters,'' Moore said. ``They know the
business. They know the problems.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
