<FIRST>r a AM-HomelessOpposition     09-24 0352</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Homeless Opposition,0361</SECOND>
<HEAD>L.A. County Spends Hundreds of Thousands to Fight Welfare Suit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The county has paid a law firm more than
$360,000 in the last year to fight allegations that homeless people
have been unfairly denied $312 a month in benefits, county records
show.
   The expenditures, mainly from funds that would otherwise be used
for welfare programs, do not include payments made during the past
three months.
   The action has drawn scathing criticism from attorneys
representing the homeless in the nearly 4-year-old case.
   ``Settling would cost a trivial amount compared to what they've
already paid,'' said Gary Blasi, an attorney for the Legal Aid
Foundation of Los Angeles, which is involved in the case.
   He estimated it would cost the county $100,000 to overhaul its
application process to one that would ensure eligible people are
not denied benefits. Estimates were not available for how much the
county might pay in additional benefits.
   ``Their top lawyers get in an hour what a general relief person
gets in a month,'' said Julie P. Downey, an assistant city attorney
also involved in the case. ``They've got to feel some kind of
uneasiness about taking public dollars, especially with the
reputation that lawyers have.''
   The private law firm retained by the county said it was hired to
defend against the lawsuit after the county counsel's office
decided it was not equipped to do so.
   ``There is undoubtedly a substantial cost involved in this
litigation, but I think it certainly involves issues that are
extremely important to the citizens of the country and the citizens
of the county,'' said Nowland C. Hong, the lead lawyer on the case.
   Lawyers for the homeless have accused the county and its
Department of Public Social Services of making the welfare
application procedure so confusing that many poor and homeless
people abandon efforts to claim benefits to which they are entitled.
   When the first part of the lawsuit was filed in 1986, Superior
Court Judge John L. Cole was among those who criticized the process.
   ``I don't understand some of the forms myself,'' he said.
</TEXT>
