<FIRST>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     09-24 0399</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Record Chill From The Plains To The Appalachians</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A large high-pressure area and lack of cloud cover contributed
to record low temperatures early Sunday from the Plains to the
central Appalachians and from the Great Lakes all the way to the
Mexican border.
   Florida, on the other hand, posted a record high temperature
along with up to 4 inches of rain.
   It was the earliest freeze on record for Fayetteville, Ark.,
which dropped to 32 degrees, and Springfield, Mo., which also hit
32. Topeka, Kan., had its second earliest freezing temperature on
record with a low of 31. It was the coldest September reading on
record at Abilene, Texas, at 38; Jackson, Ky., at 34; and Midland,
Texas, at 36.
   Nearly 50 cities reached or tied record lows Sunday morning,
including Del Rio, Texas, on the Mexican border, which cooled to 51
degrees.
   Other records included 30 at Bluefield, W.Va.; 29 at Dubuque,
Iowa; and 36 at Oklahoma City. Chicago tied its record of 35 and
Detroit tied its record of 34.
   Sunday's low in the Lower 48 states was 22 at Langdon, N.D.
   Frost and-or freeze advisories were posted late Sunday and early
Monday across northern and central Lower Michigan, and from the
central Appalachians to inland sections of New England.
   Over the desert Southwest and Florida, however, afternoon
temperatures remained in the 80s and 90s. Key West tied its record
high for the date of 92 degrees.
   The strong cold front that brought the dramatic cold to the
central and eastern sections of the nation moved well off the
Atlantic Coast, and when it moved across the middle and southern
Atlantic Coast states, it generated high wind that caused damage
and created high surf.
   Wind gusted to 65 mph late Saturday at the Chesapeake Bay Bridge
Tunnel near Norfolk, Va. Trees were damaged by high wind near
Eureka, N.C., the National Weather Service said.
   Showers and thunderstorms were confined to Florida, southern
Alabama and southern Georgia during Sunday afternoon, producing
locally heavy rain and wind as high as 40 mph.
   In Florida, Glenlea had gotten 4.29 inches of rain since
Saturday, Sandalwood got 4.38 inches, and Apalachicola received
1.20 inches in an hour and by midafternoon had recorded 4.01 inches
since morning.
   During the six hours up to 2 p.m. EDT, 2.04 inches of rain fell
at Mayport, Fla.
</TEXT>
