<FIRST>u a AM-Hugo-Guard     09-24 0547</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hugo-Guard,0563</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guardsmen Are Touched by Victims' Plight</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hugo, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELLIOTT MINOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Staff Sgt. Bill Petty cried when he saw
the desperation of people who pushed, shoved and slugged it out
while waiting hours in line to buy a bag of ice.
   ``People were pitiful. They were begging for ice,'' said Petty,
one of 1,400 South Carolina National Guardsmen mobilized in the
wake of Hurricane Hugo. ``There were fistfights in the line. They
were down-on-the ground fights - men and women.''
   In a city left without electricity and other basic services
since late Thursday, Petty and other soldiers have helped keep
order as people stand in line to buy ice or fill up jugs and
containers with fresh water.
   Petty said people began lining up at 6 a.m. Saturday when a
private company sold 50-pound bags of ice for $6 apiece. Guardsmen
and police were sent to help control the crowd, which grew to 3,000
by 2 p.m. About 500 people were still in line when the supply ran
out.
   ``Everybody waits for ice,'' he said. ``We had people in
wheelchairs. We had a woman who had recently had three (heart)
bypasses. There were rich people, poor people, whites and blacks.''
   Petty said some people left children to guard the 50-pound bags
while they went for a car and found the ice stolen when they
returned.
   ``I hope it never happens in my hometown,'' said Petty, a
businessman in Union in northern South Carolina. ``I don't mind
saying that I cried.''
   Brig. Gen. Frank Jones, commander of the guard's task force,
said many guardsmen are helping to maintain law and order in the
hurricane disaster area. Others are helping to clear streets,
remove fallen trees from power lines, operate water purification
equipment and hand out water.
   Guardsmen patrol the streets during the 7 p.m. to 7 a.m. curfew,
when the city is dark because power remains out. They are also
stationed around the clock at key locations to prevent looting.
   Staff Sgt. James W. Shugart of Lockhart, appearing tired after a
night of road patrols when the city was without lights or signs of
normal activity.
   ``It's a weird feeling. It's scary out there,'' said Shugart, a
textile mill worker. ``You don't know what to expect. There are no
lights. You don't see anything open.''
   The guardsmen are quartered near an armory by the Johnson Hagood
Stadium, where the Citadel plays football. They sleep in tents, in
trucks or beneath the stars and survive on Army field rations.
   ``The community has just been outstanding to us,'' said Jones,
president of the Davis National Bank in Mullins and commander of
the 218th Infantry Brigade. ``I was told people have offered them
food, water and bathroom facilities.''
   Jones believes the guard has made a difference in the city.
   ``I feel confident with the show of force we've had, in
conjunction with the civilian law-enforcement personnel, that it
has been helpful in deterring looting,'' Jones said.
   Spec. David McCarley of Union said he's been protecting damaged
businesses during his six- and eight-hour tours of guard duty.
   ``A lot of the stores are unsecured,'' he said. ``The people
have been real friendly. They told us they appreciate us being down
here.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
