<UNK>Columbia Hit By Water From Extingusher</UNK>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Space shuttle Columbia was sprayed
with an undetermined amount of water when a fire extinguisher
system unexpectedly came on for several minutes Sunday, NASA
reported.
   Space agency spokesman Dick Young said technicians were
examining the ship to see if any damage was done. An investigation
was under way to determine what triggered the water system, he
said. It normally would be set off by high heat.
   The mishap occurred while Columbia was in a processing building
being readied for a December flight. Young said it was too early to
determine whether that schedule would be affected.
   Young said Columbia's power was off and its two 60-foot-long
cargo bay doors were closed at the time of the incident. Damage, if
any, would be confined to thermal tiles that fit on the outside of
the vehicle and protect it from heat during re-entry into Earth's
atmosphere from orbit.
   Columbia's made its first flight in more than 3{ years last
month.
