<FIRST>u i AM-StCroix 1stLd-Writethru a0685 09-24 0717</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-St Croix, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0685,0742</SECOND>
<HEAD>St. Croix Struggles to Recover</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 5th pvs, `Two radio...' to ADD oil leak;
Pickup 6th, `The more....' SUBS graf 23 pvs `The troops...' with one graf
to RESTORE dropped letter in name; pickup graf 24 ```People just....' With
AM-Hugo</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEAN McNAIR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHRISTIANSTED, U.S. Virgin Islands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Gallows Bay Crab &amp;
Oyster House carried an encouraging sign in its window.
   ``Open,'' it read. ``Today's Special _ Food!''
   A week after Hurricane Hugo ravaged the island of St. Croix,
followed by widespread looting, dazed residents slowly are getting
their lives back in order.
   Relief supplies have arrived, power crews have begun work on
electrical lines and a few businesses have re-opened. On the
sidewalk in front of one boarded-up photo shop, a merchant sold
boxes of film from a table on Saturday.
   Two radio stations began operating again on limited power and
telephone service has been restored between St. Croix and
neighboring St. Thomas, which suffered less damage.
   Still, the hurricane's is not forgotten. A utility storage tank
damaged by the hurricane is spilling 7,000 gallons of fuel oil a
day into the waters around Christiansted, the capital of St. Croix,
the Coast Guard said Sunday.
   In all, 40,000 gallons have flowed from a storage tank at a
Virgin Islands Water and Power Authority plant containing 1.6
million gallons of No. 6 fuel oil, the Coast Guard said in a
statement.
   The Coast guard said it hoped all oil would be removed from the
tank within the next two days.
   The more than 1,100 U.S. soldiers on the island have been
directing passengers at St. Croix airport and patrolling streets in
four-wheel drive vehicles. But the looting they were called in to
control stopped days ago.
   ``There really hasn't been much looting that we've observed
since we've arrived,'' said Navy Lt. Cmdr. Steve Burnett, a
spokesman for the military contingent.
   The stores already had been stripped of their merchandise before
President Bush ordered the troops to fly to the U.S. territorial
island Thursday. Some residents complain the federal government
sent in guns when the 50,000 islanders desperately needed food.
   ``I don't see any need for this number of troops here,'' said
Dorene Carter, a nutritionist and Red Cross volunteer. ``The United
States should be ashamed.''
   Instead of roaming St. Croix with guns, the troops should be
helping rebuild the island, she said.
   Burnett said the troops were told to help local police maintain
order.
   Jan Hanley, president of the St. Croix Chamber of Commerce, said
the troops were welcome.
   ``I think we need every bit of help that we can get from the
mainland,'' she said.
   Lt. Gov. Derek Hodge said the relief response has been
tremendous, but officials are having problems getting supplies
organized and distributed. He said the troops will be used to help
rebuild the roads and bridges as well as maintain order.
   Hodge and others on the island said initial news reports about
the looting were overblown.
   ``We had no rioting,'' Hodge said, but the U.S. troops still
were needed because local police were too busy taking care of their
own families to maintain order. ``We had to fill that vacuum.''
   George Bagoon O'Reilly, a former territorial senator, said
residents panicked when they saw the damage caused by the first
hurricane to hit the island in more than 60 years.
   Some of those who looted were stealing whatever they could find,
but O'Reilly said he and others were simply salvaging food from
damaged stores.
   ``It was blacks. It was whites,'' he said. ``Everybody was
looting.''
   The troops arrived too late to serve any purpose, O'Reilly said.
   ``People just don't like it,'' he said. ``All we want now is
just some electrical power.''
   Hodge said he expects the troops will stay another week or so.
   At least one member of the U.S. military force got an early trip
home over the weekend.
   National Guard member Darren Floyd was called to the island a
day before the hurricane slammed into his hometown of Charleston,
S.C. Floyd got permission to leave so he could check on heavy
damage to his home and his family's antique business.
   ``It's kind of ironic to send me here to help these people,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
