<FIRST>u a AM-BusAccident     09-24 0654</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bus Accident,0672</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investigators Recreate Bus-Truck Collision</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLEY SHANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALTON, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grief-stricken neighbors watched Sunday as a
soft-drink delivery truck and a school bus carrying federal
investigators retraced the path of a collision that killed 20
students.
   The National Transportation Safety Board said the tests helped
determine the speed the bus was traveling Thursday on the two-lane
road in southern Texas, 15 miles from the Mexico border.
   ``We feel reasonably comfortable that the speed of the bus was
somewhere in the range of, give or take, 30 miles per hour,'' said
NTSB member Lee Dickinson.
   The speed limit on the road the bus was traveling is 55 mph.
   Dickinson said tests showed the school bus and the Dr Pepper
truck could see each other within a range of 150 feet as they
approached an intersection.
   The truck driver told authorities that his brakes failed and he
went through a stop sign, striking the bus and sending it tumbling
into the pit.
   There were 81 aboard the bus; 20 died and 61 survived. Funerals
for the last four victims were scheduled for Monday. The bus
driver, in stable condition, and two girls, in critical condition,
remained hospitalized Sunday.
   At the crash site Sunday was one of the students who escaped
from the submerged bus. Fourteen-year-old Edna Morales, who had
cuts on her neck and face and bandages on her left arm and right
leg, came in hopes it might cure her of the nightmares she has
experienced since the accident.
   Miss Morales, the last student to board the bus, told
investigators she got on the bus about 800 feet from the crash
site. Her description of the bus' acceleration helped investigators
arrive at the estimated 30 mph speed.
   For about 75 others who gathered to watch the test, Sunday's
re-enactment was yet another occasion to remember the dead students
from Mission High School and Mission Junior High. The tests were
conducted about the same time as the 7:25 a.m. accident.
   ``Who would think that this would happen in this little town?''
said Gloria Rivera, who watched the re-enactment while on her way
to deliver tamales to the family of one of the victims.
   Adrian Escobedo, 15, brought a video camera to make a tape of
the tests. Escobedo said he was a neighbor and good friend of
Michael and David Saens, two brothers killed in the wreck and
buried Saturday.
   ``I was going to show it to their mother,'' he said.
   Another friend of the Saens brothers, 17-year-old Veronica
Salinas, wept as she recalled Michael helping another student with
algebra the night before the wreck and David being excited about
playing in his first junior high football game.
   Friday's classes were canceled, as were all weekend school
activities, but the two schools were to reopen Monday.
   ``I feel that it's going to be very hard for me to go in class
with their seats empty,'' said 16-year-old Magdalee Salazar, a
Mission High School junior who knew four of the victims.
   Veronica Salinas, 17, a Mission High student who lost two close
friends in the accident, said, ``It's hard to think that one moment
they're with us and the next moment they are gone.'' Returning to
class, she added, will be ``very hard, very different.''
   In conducting the tests Sunday morning, investigators were among
42 people who boarded a school bus similar to the one involved in
the accident. They also used a Dr Pepper tractor pulling the same
trailer involved in the accident so that the trailer's brakes could
be tested. Investigators found no evidence of brake failure on the
trailer.
   A previous NTSB inspection indicated no evidence of brake system
failure on the truck, disputing truck driver Ruben Perez's claim to
Texas Department of Public Safety officers that the brakes had
failed.
   Acting on the advice of his attorney, Perez refused Saturday to
talk with NTSB officials.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
