<FIRST>r i AM-Europe-Skies     09-24 0404</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Europe-Skies,0415</SECOND>
<HEAD>European Air Traffic Congestion Worst in World, Jane's Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: For Release 8 p.m. EDT, Time set by source</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Europe's skies are the most crowded in the world,
and a single air traffic control network is needed to replace the
current patchwork system, the editor of an industry yearbook said
Monday.
   David Rider, editor of the authoritative ``Jane's Airport
Equipment,'' also said the U.S. deregulation of its airline
industry has saved American passengers $100 billion in the last 11
years.
   Rider said 42 air traffic control centers now use 22 different
systems to communicate with one another in Europe ``in a most
inefficient and time-consuming way.''
   A flight from London to Athens, for example, requires the
cooperation of seven countries and 50 air traffic controllers using
telex and telephones and spending a total of 35 manhours to arrange
the routes and timings, he said in the introduction to the latest
yearbook.
   Many bottlenecks in north-south routes stem from the absence of
a civil radar network in Greece, he said. Controllers there rely on
radio communication with pilots, meaning aircraft must stay 60
miles apart instead of three miles as they do in British airspace.
   Going east to west is not much better, he said. An aircraft
flying about 870 miles between Frankfurt to Madrid passes through
the control of seven centers.
   By contrast, in the United States, a flight of roughly the same
distance _ Chicago to Boston _ passes through only three centers,
he said.
   ``Congestion in the air as well as on the ground is a major
problem in Europe, and it is now deemed to be the worst in the
world,'' Rider wrote.
   A single, European system is the ``obvious solution,'' he said,
``but one which seems unpalatable to many countries since, if
implemented correctly, it would mean the unified control of both
civil and military airspace throughout Western Europe.''
   In his remarks on American deregulation, Rider said fares have
declined by one-fifth, after inflation is considered, because of
increased competition. However, he said increased traffic has led
to delays.
   He also said the December bombing of Pan Am Flight 103 over
Lockerbie, Scotland, has caused ``major reverberations'' with
governments, aviation authorities, airlines and airports worldwide.
   The introduction of new systems for controlling personnel and
baggage has helped reduce risk, he said.
   A total of 270 people were killed in the bombing of Flight 103.
</TEXT>
