<HEAD>Doctor in Child Custody Dispute Remains Jailed</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: SUBS 5th graf pvs, bgng: ``Morgan hid...'' to make it their
daughter; picks up 6th graf pvs, bgng: ``Elaine Mittleman...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEROY TILLMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dr. Elizabeth Morgan, jailed 25 months ago in
a bitter child custody dispute, remains jailed until a nine-member
appeals panel rules on the request for her freedom, her attorney
said Sunday.
   Attorney Adrian Roe filed the papers with the District of
Columbia Court of Appeals on Saturday, just hours after President
Bush signed a bill designed to free her.
   ``We're hopeful the court will act promptly, but we have no
guarantees,'' Roe said, adding that all the appeals judges would
have to rule on the request.
   Morgan has been held in the District of Columbia Jail since
August 1987 for failing to produce the girl for court-ordered
visits by her ex-husband and the girl's father, Dr. Eric Foretich.
   Morgan hid the girl after alleging that Foretich had sexually
abused the girl. Foretich has repeatedly denied those charges and
at one point offered a $5,000 reward to anyone who could provide
information on their daughter's whereabouts.
   Elaine Mittleman, Foretich's attorney, told The Associated Press
in a telephone interview it was unlikely that Morgan would be freed
before court opened on Monday.
   ``I would think that she wouldn't be freed until we have had
time to file papers with the court stating our side of the
argument,'' Ms. Mittleman said.
   Foretich and Ms. Mittleman have stressed that the bill does not
require Ms. Morgan to produce the couple's 7-year-old daughter,
Hilary.
   Foretich said that he wants the federal government to give him
as much assistance in finding his daughter as it has given his wife
in her effort to be freed from jail.
   ``I think that someone in our government ought to assist me to
find my daughter,'' he said. ``And if they would do that. I'd be
delighted to have Elizabeth Morgan released (from jail). But until
they're willing to do that, I don't see where I have any choice but
to concern myself with the violation of my rights and those of my
daughter.''
   He and Ms. Mittleman have said it was unfair that his ex-wife
was getting such extraordinary preferential treatment from Congress
and the President.
   Presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Saturday that Bush
signed the bill ``out of compassion for her plight'' after members
of Congress, also concerned about her case, passed legislation that
enables her to be freed.
   The congressional bill will be applied retroactively to Morgan's
case.
   The child remains hidden at an undisclosed location, although
court officials believe the girl may be with Morgan's parents in
England.
</TEXT>
