<FILEID>AP-NR-09-24-89 1953EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-St.Croix-Rebuild     09-24 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-St. Croix-Rebuild,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Interior Secretary to Set Up Groups to Aid Islands With Hurricane
Damage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interior Secretary Manuel Lujan, just back
from hurricane-ravaged St. Croix, said Sunday he will set up two
task forces to deal with the economic and environmental damages.
   ``The whole environment is really devastated,'' Lujan said in a
telephone interview. ``There's not a leaf on a tree anywhere. The
economy is flat on its back.''
   Lujan traveled over the weekend to Puerto Rico and St. Croix a
week after Hurricane Hugo swept through the Caribbean, felling
homes, downing power lines and weaving a wide swath of destruction.
   The secretary said a multi-agency group will deal with the
economic destruction as well as the environmental damages, which
included threats to the endangered Puerto Rican parrot and the
leatherback turtle. He also cited two oil leaks in St. Croix.
   A storage tank damaged by the hurricane is spilling 7,000
gallons of fuel oil a day into the waters around Christiansted, the
capital of St. Croix, the Coast Guard said Sunday.
   In all, 40,000 gallons have flowed from a storage tank at a
Virgin Islands Water and Power Authority plant containing 1.6
million gallons of No. 6 fuel oil, the Coast Guard said in a
statement.
   The Coast guard said it hoped all oil would be removed from the
tank within the next two days.
   ``Both of those (spills) are oozing oil into the ocean,'' Lujan
said. ``One of the things we're going to do ... is put together a
multi-discipline environmental assessment group to see how we deal
with all of those things.''
   To bolster the economy, the secretary said, he will seek a task
force to study ways to rebuild St. Croix's businesses and tourism
industry.
   ``All of the businesses have been damaged,'' Lujan said.
``Tourism is their primary activity and that is just dead in its
tracks. We have to get the resources of various agencies, perhaps
the small business associations, maybe HUD (Housing and Urban
Development), Farmers Home Administration, Department of Interior.''
   Lujan said he did not see any of the looting that had been
reported on St. Croix after the hurricane but said he would
recommend to President Bush that the 1,100 or so American troops
sent to help stay in place ``to allow for a little more
normalization.''
</TEXT>
