<HEAD>Mayoral Candidate `Shaken Up' in Auto Accident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayoral candidate David Dinkins was shaken up
but not seriously injured when he was involved in an auto accident
en route to a campaign appearance Sunday, an aide said.
   ``Basically it was a bump on the head,'' said Stanley Davis,
deputy press secretary for Dinkins, who is Manhattan borough
president.
   Dinkins' aide, Barbara Fife, said Dinkins and three others were
riding in a car that was broadsided by another auto.
   The candidate resumed his campaign schedule after he was treated
at Metropolitan Hospital, Davis said. Dinkins was the winner of
this month's Democratic mayoral primary, toppling Mayor Edward I.
Koch.
   Police Sgt. Raymond O'Donnell said the accident was under
investigation. Dinkin's driver and two people in the second auto
were also treated at the hospital, he said.
