<HEAD>Money, Goods, Blood, Time Donated to Help South Carolina Storm Victims</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hugo, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   People across the country were donating money, goods, blood and
time to help victims of Hurricane Hugo in South Carolina, and
Charleston Mayor Joseph Riley Jr. on Sunday said the offerings were
heartwarming.
   Riley said the city was grateful for all the help it was
receiving as it struggles to recover from Hugo's destruction.
   ``We have received so many wonderful offerings of assistance,''
he said.
   The American Red Cross sought donations of blood and money and
brought in lunch wagons from around the country to help feed the
hungry.
   The Red Cross also had 208 shelters open in South Carolina on
Saturday night, housing 46,182 people, said Chris Chidley, Red
Cross spokesman in Columbia.
   Chidley said 40 people were waiting in line Sunday afternoon at
the American Red Cross headquarters in Columbia to donate blood.
   ``The response has been tremendous,'' he said.
   The Salvation Army brought in disaster assistance units from
Florida, Georgia, North Carolina and Louisiana and was trying to
round up more from other areas.
   ``We think between our efforts and the Red Cross, we're going to
make a real difference,'' said John Edwards, spokesman for the
Salvation Army in the Carolinas.
   The Salvation Army opened a food distribution center in North
Charleston Sunday, and about 2,000 people waited in line, he said.
   About 200 University of South Carolina students and other
volunteers formed a human chain Sunday to pass donated goods into
the Carolina Coliseum.
   ``Some people who came to donate stuff have stayed to help,''
said Brad Smith, associate pastor of Spring Valley Presbyterian
Church and one of the organizers of the project. ``To see people
working together like this, it's exciting, it's beautiful.''
   Within five hours, a 10,000-square-foot room in the coliseum
that has ceilings about 12 feet high was packed with goods.
   The goods had to be sorted and a tractor-trailer was scheduled
to come Monday afternoon to take the first load of items to the
coast, Smith said.
   In Charleston, the Alabama State Baptist Convention opened a
mobile kitchen Sunday. People lined up all day in the rain, with
temperatures in the 60s.
   Emmette Jones of Montgomery, Ala., said the van would feed about
2,000 people in a day.
