<FIRST>r a AM-Bush'sSquadron     09-24 0358</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush's Squadron,0368</SECOND>
<HEAD>WWII Vets Plan Reunion, Want President</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Survivors of President Bush's World
War II Navy squadron plan a reunion they hope will feature their
most famous flyboy.
   Bush's fellow veterans from torpedo squadron VT-51, who remember
him as a quiet, 20-year-old pilot, said they'd like him to join
their effort to reunite the group here next March.
   ``Just for old times' sake,'' said Leo Nadeau, Bush's gunner.
``The majority of us haven't seen each other in 45 years, but the
memories still linger on.''
   Bush did his torpedo bomber training at the Fort Lauderdale
naval air base for three months in 1943, and recently wrote a
handful of words for a magazine about that experience.
   ``I went off to Fort Lauderdale to learn to fly,'' Bush wrote in
the September issue of Life magazine. ``Training up and down the
East Coast, dropping ... dummy bombs and torpedoes. ... I had an
ensign's stripe and an admiral's confidence. I was a Navy pilot.''
   Some believe the president will show up at the reunion, which is
being held in conjunction with an air show, especially if they are
here to greet him.
   ``Obviously, I can't any more speak for the president than the
man on the moon, but it sounds like something he'd attend,'' said
Legare Hole, who flew with Bush.
   ``As a pilot, you could always depend on George,'' said Jack
Guy, who flew with Bush for two years. He, Butchart and a dozen
others from the squadron were invited to the president's
inauguration last year.
   ``Today, I think the bond between George and his crewmen and his
fellow combat pilots is very, very strong,'' Guy said. In fact, the
president often sends them notes, he said.
   Don Rhodes, a White House aide, said Bush may be drawn to the
reunion because the comrades who flew Grumman Avenger bombers with
him will be there.
   ``He enjoyed meeting those guys at the Blair House at the
inauguration,'' Rhodes said.
   But, he said, ``there just are not enough hours in the day and
he has to say no 99.9 percent of the time.''
</TEXT>
