<SECOND>AM-Israel-Demjanjuk,0257</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Rejects Appeal Of Demjanjuk's Lawyer's Attacker</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel's Supreme Court on Sunday rejected an
appeal by a 71-year-old Holocaust survivor jailed for hurling acid
into the face of the Israeli lawyer of convicted Nazi war criminal
John Demjanjuk, Army radio said.
   Yisrael Yehezkieli appealed to the court to reduce his
three-year sentence and cut the $11,000 compensation he was ordered
to pay Yoram Sheftel, the radio said. Sheftel was injured in the
eye in the attack.
   Sheftel represented John Demjanjuk, a 69-year-old Soviet-born
autoworker from Ohio sentenced to death in April 1988 for his role
as a Nazi guard. Prosecutors said he operated the gas chambers at
the Treblinka death camp in Nazi-occupied Poland during World War
II.
   Demjanjuk said he was a victim of mistaken identity and appealed
the conviction and sentencing. The appeal is scheduled to be heard
before the Supreme Court in May 1990.
   The Supreme Court said it rejected Yehezkieli's appeal because
the attack was premeditated and caused bodily harm.
   Yehezkieli had argued the fine and sentence were excessive in
view of his advanced age and poverty.
   The acid attack occurred during the December funeral of another
Demjanjuk attorney, Dov Eitan, who committed suicide by throwing
himself out of a high-rise hotel in central Jerusalem.
   Yehezkieli, whose family was killed in Treblinka, was convicted
in March of aggravated assult.
   He attended most of the 14-month trial and was thrown out of the
courtroom several times for disrupting the proceedings.
</TEXT>
