<FIRST>r a AM-CoalStrikeRally     09-24 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Coal Strike Rally,0305</SECOND>
<HEAD>About 2,500 Labor Union Activists Rally For Striking Miners</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENWICH, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 2,500 labor union activists, many
dressed in camouflage gear, held a peaceful but emotional rally
Sunday outside Pittston Co. headquarters here in support of
striking coal miners.
   United Mine Workers' organizers said some striking miners and
supporters from seven Northeastern states gathered for the
four-hour rally to show their support for the five-month-old strike
against Pittston involving 1,700 miners in West Virginia and
Virginia.
   UMW president Richard L. Trumka stressed unity and nonviolence
in a speech before the demonstrators, who included members of the
AFL-CIO, United Auto Workers, Communication Workers of America and
the International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers.
   ``They want to separate us by geography. They want to separate
us by union label ... by the color of our skins, by our gender,
because they know that only by keeping the labor movement divided
can they win,'' Trumka said. ``We'll never again be divided.''
   Bill Casstevens, international secretary-treasurer for the
United Auto Workers, offered a pledge of solidarity. ``Your
struggle is our struggle. Your dreams are our dreams.''
   The activists from Connecticut, Massachusetts, Rhode Island,
Maine, New York, New Jersey and Pennsylvania marched from the
city's Sherman Baldwin Park about a mile to Pittston Co.
headquarters downtown.
   As the demonstrators walked, many of them wearing the camouflage
clothes the union has used to symbolize its hard-line stance, they
taunted the company saying, ``What's disgusting? Union busting.''
   Pittston offices in Greenwich and Virginia were closed Sunday,
and company officials could not be reached for comment.
   The rally was part of the union's effort to force a settlement
in the strike, which began April 5. The company wants to cut
benefits and raise wages, but the union has rejected any givebacks.
</TEXT>
