<HEAD>Violinist Wins Carnegie Hall Competition</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 34-year-old woman who teaches at the
University of California in Santa Barbara won the Carnegie Hall
International American Music Competition for Violinists on Sunday
afternoon.
   Michelle Makarski, 34, a native of White Pine, Mich., receives
$10,000, a contract with New World Records, a Grove Dictionary of
Music and Musicians and an appearance at Carnegie during the
1990-91 season with the American Symphony, for which Anthony Davis
will compose a piece of violin music.
   The competition is held every other year and is co-sponsored by
The Rockefeller Foundation. It rotates between violin, piano and
voice.
   Victor Schultz, 30, a native of Winnipeg, Canada, received the
second prize of $5,000. David Wolf, 23, native of Nogent-le-Rotrou,
France, a student of Josef Gingold at Indiana University, won the
$3,000 third prize.
   Each of 12 semi-finalists received $1,500. Seventy-five
violinists entered the competition. The semi-final competition was
held Monday and Tuesday. On Saturday, each of the three finalists
played a recital. On Sunday, each of the three played a concerto
for seven judges.
