<FIRST>u i AM-Nicaragua-Elections 2ndLd-Writethru a0790 09-24 0443</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua-Elections, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0790,0455</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sandinistas Choose Ortega As Presidential Candidate</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with Ortega nominated, no pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ruling Sandinista party late
Sunday named President Daniel Ortega to head its slate of
candidates for next year's elections and picked Vice President
Sergio Ramirez as his running mate.
   Interior Minister Tomas Borge introduced the nominations during
the daylong convention, and the 1,746 delegates approved the
choices by acclamation.
   Ortega, 44, who led the Sandinista National Liberation Front to
power with the 1979 overthrow of dictator Anastasio Somoza, had
been expected to win the nomination.
   He will run against the opposition coalition candidate, Violeta
Barrios de Chamorro, publisher of the newspaper La Prensa, in Feb.
25 elections.
   There had been uncertainty as to who would take the No. 2 spot,
with reports that Ramirez, a 47-year-old lawyer and novelist,
wanted to retire from public life. Borge had been mentioned as a
candidate for the nomination.
   Earlier, the convention approved a 31-page platform promising,
among other things, better health care, economic growth and a
``respectful accord'' with the United States.
   The platform, bearing the title ``Everyting Will Be Better,''
was also approved by acclamation, point by point, as these were
read aloud by Bayardo Arce, coordinator of the front.
   The platform promises economic growth at an annual rate of 5
percent, a halving of the infant mortality of 60 deaths per 1,000
births, and expansion of free education.
   The Nicaraguan economy, damaged by war and a U.S. economic
boycott, has become one of the poorest in Latin America. An
estimated 24 percent of Nicaragua's population of 3.5 million
cannot read or write.
   The convention, representing a wide spectrum of society, also
was to choose 90 candidates for the National Assembly _ the
single-chamber parliament _ and mayors for 145 municipalities.
   President Daniel Ortega moved up the date for the current
elections in return for a regional agreement on Aug. 7 to disband
the U.S.-supported Contra rebels who have fought to topple his
government since 1981. The Contras are to be disbanded by the end
of the year.
   There were no surprises in the Sandinista platform, which
promises to continue the current move toward ``a firm and durable
peace that will cover equally all Nicaraguan families and that will
give us security and tranquility in the future.''
   The document says the Sandinista government also seeks a
``respectful accord with the government of the United States.''
   The United States has been considering how to aid the 14-party
opposition coalition, and the Sandinistas say they expect millions
of dollars to flow to its campaign.
</TEXT>
