<FILEID>AP-NR-09-24-89 2135EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Iran-Oil     09-24 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Iran-Oil,0269</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iran Says Oil Output Averages 2 Million Barrels a Day</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran exported an average of 2 million
barrels of oil a day during recent months, Oil Minister Gholamreza
Aqazadeh has said.
   The Islamic Republic News Agency quoted him as saying that 90
percent of the oil was sold for cash rather than bartered for
goods, a development he called unprecedented since the 1979
revolution.
   The agency, monitored in Cyprus, quoted Aqazadeh as giving the
export figure Saturday but it did not specify exactly how many
months he was referring to.
   Iran has an output quota of 2.78 million barrels a day set by
the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries.
   Iran's oil output during the eight-year Gulf war with Iraq
plunged below 1 million barrels a day at times. Both belligerents
targeted each other's oil industries in an effort to cut their
economic lifelines.
   The Iranian oil minister also said the war-devastated Abadan
refinery on the Gulf coast had been rebuilt at a cost of $40
million and its capacity has reached 130,000 barrels a day.
   Aqazadeh was quoted as saying imports of refined gasoline have
stopped because domestic refineries had been rebuilt, and the
government was considering lifting gasoline rationing.
   In addition to the recent ending of gasoline imports, only a
portion of the country's needs in kerosene and gas oil were being
imported, Aqazadeh said.
   Iran will stop importing these two items after the Arak and
Bandar Abbas refineries are put back into operation, he was quoted
as saying.
</TEXT>
