<FIRST>u f BC-GasolinePrices     09-24 0217</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Gasoline Prices,0224</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lundberg Survey Notes Slight Rise in Prices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gasoline prices rose nearly a third of a
penny over the past two weeks as retailers found they no longer
could absorb prices increases from wholesalers, a survey found.
   The overall national price of a gallon of gasoline, including
all grades of the fuel along with state and local taxes, rose 0.31
cents to $1.0943 cents a gallon for the week ended Sept. 22,
according to the Lundberg Survey.
   Trilby Lundberg, director of the biweekly price poll of about
12,000 service stations nationwide, said a competitive
end-of-summer market forced retailers to hold prices down, even
though wholesalers were making increases.
   ``Now the wholesale rises have been great enough so that now
retailers have been turning up their prices, on average,'' she
said. She forecast the trend would continue into the fall, ``but
its difficult to do during a time of decreased demand.''
   Average nationwide prices per gallon at self-service gasoline
pumps, which account for more than 80 percent of all sales, were at
98.25 cents for regular unleaded; $1.1531 for premium unleaded; and
97.22 cents for regular leaded, according to the survey.
   At full-serve stations the average prices were $1.2721 for
regular unleaded, $1.3967 for premium unleaded and $1.2619 for
regular leaded.
</TEXT>
