<SECOND>PM-Time-Special,0452</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kodak To Be Sole Sponsor of Time Special Issue on Photojournalism</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Time magazine plans to publish a special issue
on the history of photojournalism next month, and the photography
giant Eastman Kodak Co. will be the lone advertiser.
   Time's special issue, ``150 Years of Photojournalism,'' will
appear Oct. 23 and will be distributed as a bonus issue to the 4.3
million regular subscribers to the weekly newsmagazine. It also
will be available at newsstands for four weeks for $2.95.
   Though it will be the first Time issue with only one sponsor,
single-advertiser magazines are nothing new.
   Time's sister magazines Fortune and People, for instance, have
had single-sponsored issues and so has Time's chief competitor,
Newsweek.
   The financial services giant Merrill Lynch &amp; Co. Inc. was the
only advertiser in a 1987 Fortune issue that featured the year's
``most exciting business people.''
   In 1984, Ford Motor Co. was the lone advertiser in a People
special issue on entertainer Michael Jackson, while Apple Computer
Inc. was the sole sponsor of Newsweek's special election issue.
   Publishers often argue that limiting advertising in a given
issue of a magazine to only one sponsor gives the sponsor a better
chance at getting its sales message across to readers. They say it
eliminates the advertising clutter that can arise in
multi-sponsored magazines.
   But it is expensive to command the single-sponsor exclusivity.
And media critics say that single-sponsorship can prompt some
readers to raise questions about editorial independence.
   Brian Brown, a Time spokesman, said Time's editors conceived the
idea for the issue as a way to mark the 150th anniversary of the
birth of photography.
   He said after the magazine decided to proceed with the issue, it
approached Kodak to see if that company wanted to be the sole
sponsor. He said Kodak had no role in shaping the issue's editorial
content.
   Neither Time nor Kodak officials would disclose how much Kodak
was paying, other than to stay it was a multimillion-dollar package.
   Kodak gets 20 pages of advertising in the 80-page issue, which
will feature scores of what Time says are the most important news
photos ever printed.
   Daniel Matthaides, a spokesman for Rochester, N.Y.-based Kodak,
said his company wanted to do something to mark the anniversary,
and felt that the Time issue would be popular with readers and that
the sole sponsorship would assert Kodak's leadership in the
photography field.
   The timing of the issue was also important, he said, because the
last three months of the year are normally a big sales season for
photographic products.
</TEXT>
